<node id="PlenOctrees">
  <data key="d0">PlenOctrees</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">PlenOctrees is a sparse octree-based representation that accelerates Neural Radiance Fields inference by densely evaluating a trained NeRF on a 3D grid, storing pruned outputs in a sparse octree, and using spherical-harmonic coefficients for view-dependent appearance.&lt;SEP&gt;PlenOctrees is the source project whose task manager is used as the basis for the provided parallel task executor.&lt;SEP&gt;PlenOctrees is an earlier method by some of the same authors and is described as the immediate methodological predecessor of Plenoxels.&lt;SEP&gt;PlenOctrees is a follow-up in the Neural Radiance Fields family associated with fast rendering.&lt;SEP&gt;PlenOctrees is a prior baked NeRF method for real-time rendering of bounded objects that does not scale to large-scale 360-degree captures.&lt;SEP&gt;PlenOctrees is a method that bakes a trained NeRF into a sparse octree of spherical-harmonic coefficients to achieve real-time rendering by trading training-time flexibility for inference speed.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-15/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876604</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural Radiance Fields">
  <data key="d0">Neural Radiance Fields</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural Radiance Fields is a research area and scene-representation framework for novel view synthesis in which a scene is modeled as a continuous volumetric function, typically parameterized by a fully connected coordinate-based multilayer perceptron (MLP). In this formulation, the representation encodes radiance-field information over space, enabling the rendering of images from new viewpoints and serving as a foundational method for view-synthesis tasks.

Neural Radiance Fields also denotes the broader technical subtopic or paper category to which several methods belong. It is the broader area associated with work such as K-Planes, MERF, and Mip-NeRF 360, and it is identified in paper or digest metadata as the subtopic covering radiance-field scene representations. In this sense, Neural Radiance Fields functions both as a specific representation paradigm and as the larger research domain centered on radiance-field-based scene modeling and rendering.

Within that broader domain, Neural Radiance Fields is also the rendering method that approaches such as PlenOctrees accelerate and approximate after baking and fine-tuning. More generally, it serves as the baseline or parent framework from which later systems derive optimizations, extensions for unbounded scenes, or alternative scene parameterizations while remaining part of the same radiance-field research lineage.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural radiance fields, abbreviated NeRF, are one of the four neural graphics primitives implemented in Instant-NGP.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural Radiance Fields is the field discussed in the digest, centered on rendering methods that evolved rapidly in speed and scene handling between 2021 and 2022.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural Radiance Fields is a subtopic and foundational field discussed through NeRF and its later extensions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-15/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876753</data>
