</node>
<node id="NeRF">
  <data key="d0">NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF most commonly refers to Neural Radiance Fields, the neural rendering and 3D scene representation method introduced by Mildenhall et al. in 2020. NeRF represents a scene with a coordinate-based multilayer perceptron that models a radiance field, which can be densely sampled on a 3D grid when needed without requiring that grid to be stored for final rendering. Its image synthesis is based on radiance-field volume rendering: each pixel is generated by tracing a single infinitesimally thin ray through the scene and evaluating a volume-rendering integral along that ray. This formulation supports robust gradient-based optimization and made NeRF a foundational method in neural 3D representation learning, widely recognized as a canonical neural radiance field baseline and as the base method revised or accelerated by later work such as Mip-NeRF, Instant-NGP, and other fast methods from 2021 to 2022 that reduced training from hours per scene to minutes or even seconds through improved encodings and fused runtimes.

NeRF is primarily designed for static scenes with consistent appearance across views and typically assumes accurate camera poses from an upstream structure-from-motion pipeline. Under those assumptions, it became a standard point of comparison across the field and a backbone or intermediate representation in many subsequent systems. It is described as the backbone used by DreamFusion, later replaced by DreamGaussian, and Magic3D uses a low-resolution NeRF in its first stage before extracting a mesh, while Magic123 replaces the NeRF representation with a differentiable mesh in its second stage. Some single-view reconstruction methods also optimize a NeRF from one image using a diffusion prior. In related work, NeRF is baked or converted into faster representations for real-time rendering, including PlenOctrees and SNeRG, and is matched in rendering quality but outpaced in training speed by alternatives such as Plenoxels. It is also fit in canonical template space in Nerfies and appears as a comparison point alongside other 3D representations.

NeRF’s limitations are also central to its role in the literature. It often learns a fuzzy volumetric density rather than a clean explicit surface, can suffer severe artifacts when appearance varies strongly across views, and its single-ray-per-pixel rendering strategy creates sampling difficulties across resolutions. It is also noted to fail in monocular dynamic-scene settings, where simultaneous viewpoints are insufficient to disambiguate motion from parallax. Because of this mix of strengths and weaknesses, NeRF remains the canonical static-scene radiance-field method against which newer and faster or more explicit approaches, including 3D Gaussian Splatting, are measured.

Separately, NeRF can also refer to a practical dataset formatting convention used in reconstruction workflows for convenient dataloading. In that distinct usage, NeRF does not denote the original Neural Radiance Fields model itself, but instead a data organization format named after it.&lt;SEP&gt;NeRF is a reference method that predicts density with an independent MLP head and serves as a comparison point for VolSDF.&lt;SEP&gt;NeRF is a neural radiance field described as a simple fully connected network trained on input views of a single scene to render new views.&lt;SEP&gt;NeRF is a neural radiance field used for view synthesis, rendering new views, extracting geometry, and representing scenes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c0c63708e1adea212beb7d6e83516771&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-501dafee6515bd66912047d0b36d43f9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-11ccc947afd3d6b02019a4d324bd68d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d1cb4f77562fea889c9e32a8c9b6b118&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-252e33536ee596bbdc69a5c1521289c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d81fdba1f24c6b674084889fda5183d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d4bb138a75a3adf4eebfac8bdf1be29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-640801c18546ebea4632cd80bbad0951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d585a450d31daf1370ab99c3ececfb44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ce2165eaaf1422a9b02235e41e20e20&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-45d73dd21f95946d74e1b943beb1d384&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ee99e1fe0369d50218c77432ff216939</data>
