<node id="MLP">
  <data key="d0">MLP</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">MLP is the neural network component of a trained NeRF whose radiance head is retrained and whose outputs are pre-tabulated before being discarded at render time.&lt;SEP&gt;MLP is the neural network component used by NeRF to evaluate density and color, which Plenoxels avoids.&lt;SEP&gt;MLP is the small decoder in MERF that converts combined grid and plane features into density and view-dependent color.&lt;SEP&gt;An MLP is the model that Instant-NGP trains and renders for each of the neural graphics primitive cases described in the text.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876504</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spherical-Harmonic Expansion">
  <data key="d0">Spherical-Harmonic Expansion</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Spherical-Harmonic Expansion is the representation used to encode view-dependent color as coefficients so that specularities can be preserved without a viewing-direction input to the MLP.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="PlenOctree">
  <data key="d0">PlenOctree</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">PlenOctree is the sparse octree artifact that stores pruned pre-tabulated MLP outputs, skips empty space, concentrates resolution near scene surfaces, and remains differentiable for direct fine-tuning.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Photometric Loss">
  <data key="d0">Photometric Loss</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Photometric Loss is an image reconstruction objective used across neural rendering, 3D reconstruction, and SLAM methods to optimize scene representations by matching rendered images or views to observed images. In general, Photometric Loss measures the discrepancy between predicted pixel values and ground-truth or reference pixel values, making it a core training or tracking signal in methods that learn from posed multi-view imagery without explicit geometry supervision.

In neural scene representation methods, Photometric Loss serves as the primary optimization target for per-scene fitting. It is the training objective used to optimize Neural Radiance Fields from posed multi-view images, and it is likewise the per-scene objective used in the 2021 “surface trilogy.” In Plenoxels, Photometric Loss is the objective against which voxel coefficients are directly optimized, while in PlenOctrees it is the objective used to fine-tune leaf coefficients after baking. In 3D Gaussian Splatting, photometric loss is also the per-scene optimization target.

Photometric Loss is additionally used in SLAM and tracking pipelines as a rendering-based alignment signal. In Co-SLAM, it supports rendering-based camera tracking, and more generally it functions as the optimization objective for tracking between the current frame and a rendered view of the current map.

The descriptions also indicate an important limitation: qualitative evidence suggests that Photometric Loss can struggle when the same Gaussian or scene element is observed across adjacent frames at radically different scales and exposure levels. This highlights that, while Photometric Loss is a widely adopted and foundational supervision signal, its effectiveness can degrade under strong appearance variation caused by scale or exposure changes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-14377/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876367</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Grid">
  <data key="d0">3D Grid</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Grid is the dense spatial structure on which a trained NeRF's MLP is evaluated before its outputs are baked into a sparse octree.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="150 FPS">
  <data key="d0">150 FPS</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">150 FPS is the reported rendering speed exceeded by PlenOctrees when rendering 800x800 frames on a single GPU.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Single GPU">
  <data key="d0">Single GPU</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Single GPU is the hardware setting on which PlenOctrees renders 800x800 frames at over 150 FPS.&lt;SEP&gt;Single GPU is the hardware setting on which Plenoxels trains in roughly 11 minutes per scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875501</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Plenoxels">
  <data key="d0">Plenoxels</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Plenoxels is an explicit radiance-field method in the Neural Radiance Fields family that represents a scene as a sparse 3D voxel grid containing densities and spherical-harmonic coefficients. Instead of relying on a NeRF-style multilayer perceptron, Plenoxels removes the neural network entirely and replaces the NeRF MLP with a directly optimized sparse voxel grid. This grid is trained from scratch by gradient descent, enabling radiance-field rendering through an explicit scene representation rather than an implicit neural one.

Within the lineage of radiance-field research, Plenoxels is described as the immediate successor to PlenOctrees and as part of the explicit-grid branch of the field. It is grouped in the same general lineage as K-Planes and is treated as prior work that helps define the explicit-representation direction intersected by later contributions. It is also characterized as a later NeRF paper in the corpus, one associated with fast rendering, and it is noted for comparing against the original bmild/nerf baseline.

Plenoxels is additionally referenced as contextual prior work in discussions of implementation details such as the position learning rate multiplier. Overall, Plenoxels is best understood as a network-free, sparse-voxel, spherical-harmonic radiance-field method that occupies an important place in the evolution from neural implicit representations toward fast, explicit grid-based rendering approaches.&lt;SEP&gt;Plenoxels is a method that pushed the speed-oriented pattern further than PlenOctrees by skipping the MLP entirely and arguing that positional features and a good optimisation prior are more important.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e7f48440bc6fda3db02b120c1e8bca82&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f03bfcd22d34d1827ec44d4dfcce42df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eaaf691c43304c4a589967639d84b94f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/bmild-nerf/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/graphdeco-inria-gaussian-splatting/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-15/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876604</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MERF">
  <data key="d0">MERF</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">MERF is a subsequent baking pipeline in which the factorization of occupancy octree plus spherical-harmonic appearance recurs.&lt;SEP&gt;MERF is a 2023 work by Reiser et al. described as a memory-efficient variant for unbounded scenes, using a tri-plane plus sparse 3D grid structure that K-Planes generalises to time.&lt;SEP&gt;MERF is a subsequent system in the corpus that targets the same unbounded radiance-field regime and uses the Mip-NeRF360 dataset.&lt;SEP&gt;MERF is a memory-efficient baked radiance-field representation for real-time view synthesis in unbounded scenes that enables interactive browser rendering within the memory budget of consumer GPUs.&lt;SEP&gt;MERF is a later system in the corpus that reuses the multiresolution hash grid encoding.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ce2165eaaf1422a9b02235e41e20e20</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876671</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SNeRG">
  <data key="d0">SNeRG</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SNeRG is a subsequent baking pipeline in which the factorization of occupancy octree plus spherical-harmonic appearance recurs.&lt;SEP&gt;SNeRG is a prior baked NeRF method for real-time rendering of bounded objects that does not scale to large-scale 360-degree captures.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Occupancy Octree Plus SH Appearance">
  <data key="d0">Occupancy Octree Plus SH Appearance</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Occupancy Octree Plus SH Appearance is the factorized representation that combines an occupancy octree with spherical-harmonic appearance and recurs in PlenOctrees and later baking pipelines.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Real-Time Rendering">
  <data key="d0">Real-Time Rendering</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Real-Time Rendering is the rendering objective emphasized by the paper and achieved by the PlenOctrees representation at interactive frame rates.&lt;SEP&gt;Real-Time Rendering is the performance objective that MERF is designed to achieve for large-scale unbounded scenes.&lt;SEP&gt;Real-Time Rendering is a capability retained by 2D Gaussian Splatting alongside fast training speed.&lt;SEP&gt;Real-time rendering is the rendering capability preserved by Feature 3DGS while adding semantic feature outputs.&lt;SEP&gt;Real-Time Rendering is the performance objective in which the method is reported to be competitive with or better than prior dynamic methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c8d46282ec234e9b7dfd7ddc08a05b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-03203/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876987</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="FPS">
  <data key="d0">FPS</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">FPS is the performance metric used to report the rendering speed achieved by PlenOctrees.&lt;SEP&gt;FPS is the evaluation metric used to express inference speed for MVSplat.&lt;SEP&gt;FPS is the rendering speed metric used in the paper, which reports at least 30 FPS at 1080p.&lt;SEP&gt;FPS is the runtime metric listed in the paper metadata and used to report rendering speed.&lt;SEP&gt;FPS is the evaluation metric listed for measuring the rendering performance reported for the method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-efee674c2ffd20246abfb52e90ffa964&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26c994414b7985eeccba7c9a66fd05d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d445282e0f2225e2a32ef51280563a09&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb7662ca60286f5c929b6bb92d667dfd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-14024/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-14627/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2308-04079/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2310-08528/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876987</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="How Robust Is Multi-View Consistency Under Fast Camera Motion?">
  <data key="d0">How Robust Is Multi-View Consistency Under Fast Camera Motion?</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">How Robust Is Multi-View Consistency Under Fast Camera Motion? is an open question about whether multi-view consistency remains reliable when cameras move quickly in splatting-based and SLAM systems.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-View Consistency">
  <data key="d0">Multi-View Consistency</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Multi-View Consistency is the property under examination, concerning whether observations from multiple frames remain coherent under fast camera motion.&lt;SEP&gt;Multi-View Consistency is a referenced detailed discussion concerning whether systems hold up under the capture conditions assumed by the splatting paradigm.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a4716f0532d6b5d940a3893a269cfdc9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fast Camera Motion">
  <data key="d0">Fast Camera Motion</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Fast Camera Motion refers to rapid camera movement that can involve sub-second pans, aggressive motion, and motion blur, creating difficult conditions for splatting-based methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">3D Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Gaussian Splatting is a 2023 scene representation and rendering method, as well as a broader research subtopic and representation family focused on modeling 3D scenes with explicit anisotropic Gaussian primitives and rendering them through fast, differentiable, rasterization-based splatting. In its foundational form, it represents a scene as a set of 3D Gaussians and uses front-to-back rasterization to enable real-time novel view synthesis while preserving training-time visual quality. It became a major alternative to NeRF on static-scene benchmarks such as Mip-NeRF 360 and is widely seen as having shifted the field toward explicit primitive-based methods because it achieved strong image quality with much faster rendering. It is also described as outperforming Instant-NGP in quality at comparable frame rates and in fidelity at 1080p.

In its standard formulation, 3D Gaussian Splatting is typically a per-scene optimization method in which Gaussian primitives are trained using photometric objectives and managed through density-control procedures. This approach produces a real-time renderable explicit model and has been adopted in place of NeRF backbones in systems such as DreamGaussian. At the same time, the vanilla method is often characterized as an unstructured optimized primitive cloud with many redundant primitives, which can contribute to overfitting to training views. Because of this structure, it is often considered less suitable when accurate geometry is required, and its output is regarded as difficult to convert into a mesh despite its high rendering quality.

Beyond standalone static-scene view synthesis, 3D Gaussian Splatting has developed into a broader framework for reconstruction, SLAM, and dynamic-scene modeling. It serves as the underlying scene representation in systems such as GS-SLAM, where its speed advantages build on prior offline reconstruction uses, and later SLAM descendants often assume reasonably smooth camera trajectories. It also functions as the base static-scene framework for dynamic extensions such as 4DGaussians.

As a research category, 3D Gaussian Splatting encompasses a wider ecosystem of methods that either optimize Gaussian primitives directly or predict them from images. It is the representation family used by AGG, the optimization and scene representation target refined by LucidDreamer into a final real-time explicit model, and the rendering target for approaches such as MVSplat that infer Gaussian parameters from sparse multi-view images. Work such as latentSplat is also categorized under this subtopic. More broadly, 3D Gaussian Splatting is treated both as a specific method and as the broader rendering representation and pipeline ecosystem built around Gaussian-based radiance fields for unbounded-scene modeling.&lt;SEP&gt;3D Gaussian Splatting is the rendering method that Feature 3DGS extends from colour rendering to feature field distillation.&lt;SEP&gt;3D Gaussian Splatting is the base rendering approach that 4DRotorGS extends for dynamic scene modelling and splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4b8d422b0944627b01e7c77ba8f039d8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eeca9db1414daed89ce6cb97dc521320&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26c994414b7985eeccba7c9a66fd05d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b4a36dbf1bfe982e8516ef5fb0a1dd0e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d81fdba1f24c6b674084889fda5183d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d445282e0f2225e2a32ef51280563a09&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d585a450d31daf1370ab99c3ececfb44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c8d46282ec234e9b7dfd7ddc08a05b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-00109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/hustvl-4dgaussians/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-14627/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-16292/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2401-04099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2308-04079/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/dreamgaussian-dreamgaussian/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-15/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-03203/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876985</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Visual SLAM">
  <data key="d0">Visual SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Visual SLAM is a sub-topic context for the question and includes systems that estimate camera motion and scene structure from visual input.&lt;SEP&gt;Visual SLAM is a mapping and tracking field that is described as being absorbed by Gaussian-splatting-based systems.&lt;SEP&gt;Visual SLAM is a field to which the paper connects the radiance-field literature.&lt;SEP&gt;Visual SLAM is the problem setting in which camera motion and scene structure are estimated from visual input, and DROID-SLAM is presented as a deep system for this task.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-252e33536ee596bbdc69a5c1521289c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-06405/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876760</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MVS">
  <data key="d0">MVS</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">MVS is a sub-topic context for the question and refers to multi-view scene reconstruction from images.&lt;SEP&gt;MVS is part of the paper's stated sub-topic, alongside Visual SLAM and MVS.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Base 3DGS Paper">
  <data key="d0">Base 3DGS Paper</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Base 3DGS Paper is the original 3D Gaussian Splatting paper that reports 30+ FPS results on Mip-NeRF 360 captures with high image overlap and quasi-static motion.&lt;SEP&gt;The base 3DGS paper is the earlier paper from which later Gaussian-Splatting SLAM systems retain the differentiable rasteriser.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mip-NeRF 360">
  <data key="d0">Mip-NeRF 360</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Mip-NeRF 360 is a dataset or capture setting with tripod-paced orbit captures, high image overlap, and essentially quasi-static camera motion.&lt;SEP&gt;Mip-NeRF 360 is a later NeRF paper in the corpus that compares against the bmild/nerf baseline.&lt;SEP&gt;Mip-NeRF 360 is the benchmark on which 3D Gaussian Splatting achieved the headline result of real-time performance at training-time quality.&lt;SEP&gt;Mip-NeRF 360 is a follow-up method to Mip-NeRF introduced in 2021 for unbounded scenes.&lt;SEP&gt;Mip-NeRF 360 is a radiance-field method that made large-scale 360-degree captures tractable to reconstruct and serves as a quality reference for MERF.&lt;SEP&gt;Mip-NeRF 360 is an extension of Mip-NeRF for unbounded scenes that uses a non-linear contraction of space and a proposal-network sampler.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e7f48440bc6fda3db02b120c1e8bca82&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec770f62777c513047108cb79ba7aa75</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/bmild-nerf/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-15/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876604</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="GS-SLAM">
  <data key="d0">GS-SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">GS-SLAM is a splatting-based SLAM system that reports tracking accuracy on Replica and TUM-RGBD benchmarks.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a late-2023 Gaussian-splatting SLAM paper that substitutes a Gaussian map into the standard online SLAM pipeline.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a GaussianSplatting-based neural SLAM variant mentioned as part of a later wave of systems.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a Gaussian-Splatting SLAM system that swaps implicit volumes for explicit 3D Gaussians, retains the differentiable rasteriser from the base 3DGS paper, and adds online keyframe management.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a SLAM system mentioned as reusing or imitating gsplat's rasteriser interface.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a broadly contemporary Gaussian-based SLAM system by Yan et al. that focuses on RGB-D.&lt;SEP&gt;GS-SLAM is a dense RGB-D SLAM system that uses 3D Gaussian Splatting as the underlying scene representation and operates with separate tracking and mapping loops.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-14377/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876847</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MonoGS">
  <data key="d0">MonoGS</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">MonoGS is a Gaussian Splatting SLAM system that reports tracking accuracy on Replica and TUM-RGBD benchmarks.&lt;SEP&gt;MonoGS is a late-2023 Gaussian-splatting SLAM paper that reports the highest-fidelity photometric reconstructions among monocular SLAM systems in the corpus.&lt;SEP&gt;MonoGS is a Gaussian-Splatting SLAM system that swaps implicit volumes for explicit 3D Gaussians, retains the differentiable rasteriser from the base 3DGS paper, adds online keyframe management, and reports the highest-quality photometric reconstructions among monocular SLAM systems in the corpus.&lt;SEP&gt;MonoGS is the first SLAM system described in the text to use 3D GaussianSplatting as its sole scene representation in the monocular setting, supporting tracking, mapping, and novel view synthesis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Replica">
  <data key="d0">Replica</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Replica is a benchmark used to evaluate tracking accuracy for splatting-SLAM systems and is described as having well-behaved trajectories.&lt;SEP&gt;Replica is a dataset used to evaluate Co-SLAM.&lt;SEP&gt;Replica is a dataset used in experiments evaluating the tracking accuracy and rendering quality of Point-SLAM.&lt;SEP&gt;Replica is one of the challenging datasets on which NICE-SLAM is evaluated.&lt;SEP&gt;Replica is a benchmark dataset on which MonoSDF is reported to substantially improve over prior methods.&lt;SEP&gt;Replica is a dataset on which GS-SLAM is evaluated for tracking accuracy and rendering quality.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a914c77868426e1f8d5848af2165c17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-14377/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-04278/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876848</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="TUM-RGBD">
  <data key="d0">TUM-RGBD</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">TUM-RGBD is an RGB-D dataset and benchmark widely used to evaluate SLAM systems, particularly for camera tracking accuracy and, in some cases, rendering quality. It is explicitly used in experiments for Co-SLAM, Point-SLAM, GS-SLAM, NICE-SLAM, DROID-SLAM, and splatting-SLAM systems, and it is also supported by repository evaluation scripts as a standard evaluation dataset.

Across these uses, TUM-RGBD serves as a reference benchmark for comparing robustness and performance under challenging conditions. It has been described as containing well-behaved trajectories in the context of evaluating splatting-SLAM tracking accuracy, while also being considered challenging enough to test systems such as NICE-SLAM. In evaluations on TUM-RGBD, Point-SLAM and GS-SLAM use it to measure both tracking accuracy and rendering quality, and DROID-SLAM is characterized as robust on this benchmark, whereas classical baselines are reported to suffer catastrophic tracking failures.

TUM-RGBD is also described as a dataset of RGB-D sequences used for monocular evaluation, indicating that beyond general RGB-D SLAM benchmarking, it can support specific evaluation settings depending on the method and protocol being tested. Overall, TUM-RGBD functions as a standard, versatile benchmark for assessing the robustness, accuracy, and visual reconstruction quality of modern SLAM approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a914c77868426e1f8d5848af2165c17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-589b580dce9f23cba1db6f4f68a4ae77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-14377/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-04278/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876884</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DROID-SLAM">
  <data key="d0">DROID-SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DROID-SLAM is a deep visual SLAM system for monocular, stereo, and RGB-D cameras that serves as a prominent end-to-end learned baseline in the literature. It is described as a later system by the same first author that extends the DeepV2D design into full SLAM by performing differentiable optimization over a growing keyframe graph. In practice, DROID-SLAM combines recurrent optical-flow-style update operators with dense or deep bundle adjustment, jointly refining depth and camera pose through a differentiable optimization layer.

Architecturally, DROID-SLAM retains a dense photometric residual tradition associated with earlier geometric methods, but replaces a hand-engineered front end with a recurrent neural network. Its defining strength is the use of learned features within deep bundle adjustment, which makes it highly robust and helps explain why it is often treated as a tracking-accuracy reference or a strong classical-geometry-style baseline despite being a learned system. It is also repeatedly compared with Direct Sparse Odometry, highlighting both continuity with and departure from earlier visual odometry pipelines.

Within broader SLAM comparisons, DROID-SLAM is frequently used as a benchmark against newer splatting-SLAM systems, especially on more difficult datasets such as EuRoC and TartanAir, where aggressive motion is part of the evaluation protocol. In the corpus, it is also positioned alongside NICE-SLAM as a contrasting counterpart for online SLAM with neural representations, with the two methods representing opposite ends of the explicit-implicit design spectrum. Beyond the method itself, its accompanying materials reportedly provide code, demos, training procedures, and evaluation workflows, reinforcing its role as a practical and widely used reference system.&lt;SEP&gt;DROID-SLAM is a later line of work that is described as being seeded by DeepV2D.&lt;SEP&gt;DROID-SLAM is a deep visual SLAM system that replaces the hand-engineered front end of classical pipelines with a recurrent neural network and a differentiable Dense Bundle Adjustment layer, and it operates on monocular, stereo, and RGB-D camera streams.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-77b518713f90adb54fa0bd6ae785bcff&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5ec848be5aa6ee5cc0be08acd6f5935&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-833bec7f18854880457df56d1a16dbb7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-1812-04605/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-1607-02565/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876760</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="EuRoC">
  <data key="d0">EuRoC</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">EuRoC is a benchmark with aggressive motion as part of the evaluation protocol.&lt;SEP&gt;EuRoC is a dataset used for monocular and stereo evaluation and can be run on a 1080Ti GPU.&lt;SEP&gt;EuRoC is a dataset supported by the DROID-SLAM evaluation scripts and can be run on a 1080Ti according to the README.&lt;SEP&gt;EuRoC is an evaluation dataset supported by the repository's evaluation scripts.&lt;SEP&gt;EuRoC is a benchmark on which DROID-SLAM is described as robust while classical baselines suffer catastrophic tracking failures.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-833bec7f18854880457df56d1a16dbb7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-589b580dce9f23cba1db6f4f68a4ae77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="TartanAir">
  <data key="d0">TartanAir</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">TartanAir is a benchmark with aggressive motion as part of the evaluation protocol.&lt;SEP&gt;TartanAir is a dataset whose data was used to train the model.&lt;SEP&gt;TartanAir is a dataset used for evaluation and training, with test, validation, monocular, and stereo data referenced in the text.&lt;SEP&gt;TartanAir is a dataset supported by the DROID-SLAM evaluation scripts and is stated to require 24G of memory.&lt;SEP&gt;TartanAir is an evaluation dataset supported by the repository's evaluation scripts.&lt;SEP&gt;TartanAir is a benchmark on which DROID-SLAM is described as robust while classical baselines suffer catastrophic tracking failures.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-833bec7f18854880457df56d1a16dbb7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-589b580dce9f23cba1db6f4f68a4ae77&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5160cf1bfca5ef8dc4dd9f099386ea9e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Gaussian">
  <data key="d0">3D Gaussian</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Gaussian is a primitive whose anisotropic covariance is optimized to match a particular projected footprint in screen space.&lt;SEP&gt;A 3D Gaussian is a volumetric primitive whose silhouette changes shape across camera angles, causing view-inconsistent inferred surfaces.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876588</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anisotropic Covariance">
  <data key="d0">Anisotropic Covariance</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Anisotropic Covariance is the parameterization of a 3D Gaussian that is optimized to fit a projected screen-space footprint.&lt;SEP&gt;Anisotropic Covariance is one of the Gaussian primitive parameters jointly predicted by MVSplat together with Gaussian centres.&lt;SEP&gt;Anisotropic covariance is optimized in the method to achieve an accurate representation of the scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26c994414b7985eeccba7c9a66fd05d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-41e2a18164d88d58975577aab63d7325</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-14627/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/graphdeco-inria-gaussian-splatting/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875511</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Motion Blur">
  <data key="d0">Motion Blur</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Motion Blur spreads radiance across pixels that were not part of a primitive's original support during fast motion.&lt;SEP&gt;Motion Blur is a source of degraded image quality that should be reduced by moving slowly during capture.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Densification Schedule">
  <data key="d0">Densification Schedule</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Densification Schedule is the mechanism that clones primitives to cover blur and later requires pruning when camera motion slows down.&lt;SEP&gt;Densification Schedule is the procedure governing primitive growth, and it is described as not being designed for linear growth in temporal trajectories.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874606</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Revising-Densification">
  <data key="d0">Revising-Densification</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Revising-Densification is a research line that has started questioning densification behavior even in the static case.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/multi-view-consistency.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874494</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NICE-SLAM">
  <data key="d0">NICE-SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NICE-SLAM is a 2021 neural, dense, online SLAM system that is commonly described as an early or starting point in the neural-SLAM and neural-implicit SLAM line of work. It jointly tracks the camera and reconstructs the scene through an implicit neural representation, and it is frequently used as a baseline or comparison point in later evaluations alongside systems such as DROID-SLAM, MonoGS, GS-SLAM, and Point-SLAM.

Across the descriptions, NICE-SLAM is characterized by its use of structured grid-based scene encoding rather than relying on a single shared scene-wide MLP. More specifically, it is described as using a scalable hierarchical feature or voxel grid that is optimized online for both mapping and tracking. It is also noted as using a small active-keyframe window for optimization. One description refers to NICE-SLAM as using a fixed-resolution grid encoding, and another says it reuses a multiresolution hash grid encoding; these statements can be understood as alternate emphases within the broader family of grid-based neural scene representations associated with the system, though the dominant characterization in the provided material is the hierarchical grid design.

NICE-SLAM is also presented as an important reference point in the evolution of dense neural SLAM methods, particularly in discussions of memory efficiency and architectural tradeoffs. In that role, it serves both as a foundational neural-implicit SLAM method and as a benchmarked prior system against which later approaches measure tracking, mapping, and memory behavior.&lt;SEP&gt;NICE-SLAM is a radiance-field-based mapping system that uses DROID-SLAM code as a front end.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-66ed01dbc31011eafae7c28b8ced18bd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a914c77868426e1f8d5848af2165c17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ce2165eaaf1422a9b02235e41e20e20&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
