</node>
<node id="LRM">
  <data key="d0">LRM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">LRM is a large reconstruction model introduced in 2023 by Hong et al. as a feed-forward single-image-to-3D method. It trains a very large transformer on Objaverse to infer a triplane radiance field, producing a NeRF-style 3D reconstruction from a single input image in roughly five seconds. A central characteristic of LRM is that it avoids per-scene optimization and does not rely on an SDS loop, which positioned it as an important example of reconstruction-based 3D generation rather than iterative test-time fitting.

LRM is frequently cited as part of the line of work arguing that high-quality 3D reconstruction may not require expensive per-scene optimization. In comparative discussions, it is treated as a feed-forward baseline and is benchmarked head-to-head against methods such as SDS-on-splats. It is also described as appearing after Magic123 in the development of single-image-to-3D methods, reinforcing its place in the progression from optimization-heavy pipelines toward faster direct inference models.

LRM also serves as a reference point for later systems and model designs. It is described as the closed paper for which TripoSR is presented as an open-weights alternative, and its large-reconstruction-model style is cited as the design basis for the Instant3D sparse-view reconstructor. At the same time, LRM has been noted to have training-time compute that scales poorly with output resolution, a limitation that later work highlights when comparing alternative feed-forward 3D generation approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21872029f2f74d4a8d748cb5926862f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a4716f0532d6b5d940a3893a269cfdc9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-11ccc947afd3d6b02019a4d324bd68d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22bc14784620637c470939b2097cd200&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2dd7bc6ade0fccf24f57100e1dd5adb7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/vast-ai-research-triposr/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2306-17843/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-06214/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-05054/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778877019</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="LGM">
  <data key="d0">LGM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">LGM is a feed-forward 3D reconstruction and generation model that adapts ideas from the LRM line of work to a Gaussian splatting representation. It ports the feed-forward reconstruction architecture onto splats by replacing an implicit radiance field with a multi-view Gaussian representation and predicting Gaussians directly from sparse multi-view inputs. In this sense, LGM is commonly characterized as a feed-forward Gaussian predictor and generator.

Within the broader landscape of 3D methods, LGM is consistently grouped with other fast feed-forward approaches rather than optimization-heavy pipelines. It is described as part of the broader family that includes methods such as AGG, and as one of the methods for which MVSplat has become an important reference point. LGM is also identified as later work that follows the same general fast Text-to-3D template as Instant3D, indicating its place in a trend toward efficient, direct generation methods.

In benchmarking and comparative evaluation, LGM is frequently used as a head-to-head feed-forward baseline, including against approaches such as SDS-on-splats. It is also noted for widely using TripoSR as a comparison baseline, reinforcing its role as a representative feed-forward method in experimental comparisons across Gaussian-based and related 3D reconstruction systems.&lt;SEP&gt;LGM is a feed-forward Gaussian generator enabled downstream by the Diffusion-based 3D Generation section opened by DreamGaussian.&lt;SEP&gt;LGM is a later feed-forward Gaussian-based generator motivated by DreamGaussian.&lt;SEP&gt;LGM is a system referenced as having a GaussianSplatting head similar to the alternative downstream head used with TripoSR.&lt;SEP&gt;LGM is a feed-forward 3D generator that produces high-resolution 3D content from either a text prompt or a single input image by predicting multi-view Gaussian features in image space.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-21872029f2f74d4a8d748cb5926862f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26c994414b7985eeccba7c9a66fd05d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-faebadc81c39822f071629969e8b6a2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22bc14784620637c470939b2097cd200&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d81fdba1f24c6b674084889fda5183d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d585a450d31daf1370ab99c3ececfb44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8d7bbefe39a52948bd9d7195856ac2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-da7ad32a7899b18880ae81f4444362ce&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2dd7bc6ade0fccf24f57100e1dd5adb7</data>
