  <data key="d5">1778876990</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Triplane Radiance Field">
  <data key="d0">Triplane Radiance Field</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A Triplane Radiance Field is the 3D representation produced by LRM from a single image.&lt;SEP&gt;A triplane radiance field is the 3D representation produced by LRM from a single image.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF Backbone">
  <data key="d0">NeRF Backbone</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The NeRF Backbone is the earlier representation that splatting is described as having absorbed.&lt;SEP&gt;NeRF Backbone is the rendering backbone in Stable-Dreamfusion and is implemented with a multi-resolution grid encoder.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cee14ff0001178656f392a3bf199e70c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875660</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Inference-Cost-Vs-Fidelity">
  <data key="d0">Inference-Cost-Vs-Fidelity</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Inference-Cost-Vs-Fidelity is a question document that articulates the benchmark gap between feed-forward and SDS-on-splats regimes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874519</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Feature 3DGS">
  <data key="d0">Feature 3DGS</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Feature 3DGS is a paper whose central trick is distilling a 2D foundation feature into 3D Gaussian primitives, and it is described as orthogonal to both the SDS and feed-forward axes.&lt;SEP&gt;Feature 3DGS is a downstream method that plugs into the CUDA kernels of Gsplat.&lt;SEP&gt;Feature 3DGS is a paper that extends 3D Gaussian Splatting beyond colour rendering to arbitrary-channel feature field distillation while preserving real-time rendering and enabling distilled semantic features as a renderer output.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50e33da257497d62c9963654a61913d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c8d46282ec234e9b7dfd7ddc08a05b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nerfstudio-project-gsplat/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-03203/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876922</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="2D Foundation Feature">
  <data key="d0">2D Foundation Feature</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A 2D Foundation Feature is the feature type distilled by Feature 3DGS into 3D Gaussian primitives.&lt;SEP&gt;A 2D foundation feature is described as something that can be distilled into 3D Gaussian primitives, and the trick is presented as orthogonal to two existing axes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Gaussian Primitives">
  <data key="d0">3D Gaussian Primitives</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Gaussian Primitives are the target primitives into which Feature 3DGS distills 2D foundation features.&lt;SEP&gt;3D Gaussian primitives are explicit 3D elements that can receive distilled 2D foundation features and serve as a substrate for 3D-aware foundation features.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Splatting Representations">
  <data key="d0">Splatting Representations</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Splatting Representations are presented as a substrate for 3D-aware foundation features generally, not only for view synthesis.&lt;SEP&gt;Splatting representations are presented as a possible substrate for 3D-aware foundation features beyond view synthesis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nerfies">
  <data key="d0">Nerfies</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Nerfies refers to two related but distinct concepts in this corpus: a dynamic radiance-field method and a dataset organization format used for scene preparation.

As a method, Nerfies is a 2020 work by Park et al. and is treated as a canonical dynamic or 4D reconstruction approach. It is described as one of the parent deformable-NeRF models, built around per-observation warps that map observed points into a single canonical radiance field or template. Within the corpus, Nerfies is associated with dynamic radiance fields and is paired with K-Planes for comparison. It is also noted as an earlier deformable radiance-field model that works well for elastic deformation but breaks down when topological changes occur. In addition, Nerfies is cited as a concurrent work that used a similar coarse-to-fine frequency strategy for deformation fields. Quantitatively, it is reported on short selfie-video scenes captured indoors with a single moving subject, and it is explicitly placed within the dynamic and 4D line discussed in the weekly synthesis.

As a dataset format, Nerfies refers to the directory and scene-organization structure used when arranging downloaded scenes. In the data-preparation instructions, HyperNeRF scenes are expected to follow this Nerfies dataset organization format.&lt;SEP&gt;Nerfies is a follow-up in the Neural Radiance Fields family associated with deformable scenes.&lt;SEP&gt;Nerfies is a NeRF variant designed to handle non-rigidly deforming subjects captured casually with a handheld phone by mapping observations into a canonical template space with a learned deformation field.&lt;SEP&gt;Nerfies is a deformable-NeRF paper presented as an entry point for modeling dynamic scenes through a canonical radiance field and deformation field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e871ba692ecdc2269f6f148bf3849940&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-252e33536ee596bbdc69a5c1521289c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-758b48d0e0102138cc11ccffdb5fff60&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e94987ca7ac98962142f83ef53476d0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-640801c18546ebea4632cd80bbad0951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-13228/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-06405/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/hustvl-4dgaussians/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2011-12948/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876753</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Splatting-Native SDS Variants">
  <data key="d0">Splatting-Native SDS Variants</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Splatting-Native SDS Variants are described as one of the two replacements competing for the role previously held by the SDS distillation paradigm by making distillation cheap enough to remain practical.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Scene Optimisation">
  <data key="d0">Per-Scene Optimisation</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-Scene Optimisation is the asset-specific optimization process used in the SDS line and is described as being skipped entirely by feed-forward reconstruction models.&lt;SEP&gt;Per-scene optimisation is the historically dominant architectural approach for 3D reconstruction in which parameters are optimised separately for each scene or asset.&lt;SEP&gt;Per-Scene Optimisation is the optimisation process that MVSplat and latentSplat eliminate and that the large reconstruction model line questions as necessary.&lt;SEP&gt;Per-scene optimisation is an earlier 3D reconstruction paradigm that the paper is said to displace in favor of amortised inference.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a4716f0532d6b5d940a3893a269cfdc9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-faebadc81c39822f071629969e8b6a2b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-04400/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875722</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-View Diffusion Model">
  <data key="d0">Multi-View Diffusion Model</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A Multi-View Diffusion Model is the component that Instant3D chains into an LRM to make the input less ambiguous.&lt;SEP&gt;Multi-view diffusion model is the model whose four-view output is used as input by Instant3D in the Large Reconstruction Model family.&lt;SEP&gt;Multi-View Diffusion Model is the first stage of the LGM pipeline that produces consistent views of the target object from a prompt or input image.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-faebadc81c39822f071629969e8b6a2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2dd7bc6ade0fccf24f57100e1dd5adb7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-04400/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-05054/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778877008</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="View Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">View Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">View synthesis is presented as one application area that splatting representations can support, but not the only one.&lt;SEP&gt;View Synthesis is the task for which splatting representations are described as a substrate, though the synthesis argues that their use extends beyond that task.&lt;SEP&gt;View synthesis is the task at which radiance fields are described as performing well.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-b3dc42246e28acdc27923c03fab11c12&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D-Aware Foundation Features">
  <data key="d0">3D-Aware Foundation Features</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">3D-aware foundation features are described as a broader direction enabled by using splatting representations as a substrate.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="HyperNeRF">
  <data key="d0">HyperNeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">HyperNeRF is a 2021 neural radiance field method introduced by Park et al. as a direct follow-up to Nerfies for modeling deformable, dynamic scenes. It is part of the Neural Radiance Fields family and is commonly characterized as one of the key early “deformable-NeRF” approaches built around per-observation warps of a canonical radiance field. HyperNeRF generalizes the canonical-template-plus-deformation-field formulation used in earlier dynamic NeRF work by introducing a higher-dimensional canonical-space representation, allowing the method to handle scenes with topological change rather than only smooth deformations.

In technical terms, HyperNeRF extends the deformation-field framework so that dynamic reconstruction remains feasible even when scene structure changes in ways that standard canonical-field warping cannot easily represent. This makes it a dynamic radiance field method designed for real dynamic scenes, while still operating at the same short-input scale as Nerfies. Within the broader corpus, it is also treated as a dynamic-radiance-field baseline or companion method alongside approaches such as K-Planes.

HyperNeRF can also refer not only to the method or paper itself but to the associated project resources and dataset source used for real dynamic scenes. In project data-preparation contexts, the HyperNeRF dataset is cited as the source of real dynamic-scene data, indicating that the name encompasses both the research contribution and the practical benchmark data released with it.&lt;SEP&gt;HyperNeRF is a follow-up method cited as part of the wave of work seeded by the paper and is also represented in the corpus.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e871ba692ecdc2269f6f148bf3849940&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-758b48d0e0102138cc11ccffdb5fff60&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e94987ca7ac98962142f83ef53476d0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-640801c18546ebea4632cd80bbad0951&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-13228/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/hustvl-4dgaussians/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2011-12948/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Deformable-NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Deformable-NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Deformable-NeRF is described as a line of methods built on per-observation warps of a canonical field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Canonical Field">
  <data key="d0">Canonical Field</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A canonical field is the reference field used in deformable-NeRF approaches, with per-observation warps applied to it.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video is a 2021 work by Gao et al. described as the monocular companion within the dynamic line.&lt;SEP&gt;Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video is a dynamic reconstruction method described as similar in scale and setting to Nerfies and HyperNeRF.&lt;SEP&gt;Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video is a paper published on 2021-05-13 that presents a method for space-time novel view synthesis from a single monocular video of a dynamic scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="K-Planes">
  <data key="d0">K-Planes</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">K-Planes is a 2023 work by Fridovich-Keil et al. that factorises 4D into six explicit feature planes as a tractable alternative to a 4D MLP.&lt;SEP&gt;K-Planes is a dynamic scene method whose planar factorisation makes memory growth linear in time rather than quadratic, and whose public results are still on minutes-or-less captures.&lt;SEP&gt;K-Planes is a factorized explicit representation for radiance fields that uses feature planes over pairs of axes, combines sampled features by element-wise multiplication, and decodes them into density and color.&lt;SEP&gt;K-Planes is a factorized representation whose decomposition pattern is mirrored by MERF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D">
  <data key="d0">4D</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">4D refers to the dynamic spatiotemporal setting that K-Planes factorises into six explicit feature planes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Explicit Feature Planes">
  <data key="d0">Explicit Feature Planes</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Explicit feature planes are the six planes used by K-Planes to factorise 4D in a tractable form.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D MLP">
  <data key="d0">4D MLP</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A 4D MLP is described as the alternative that K-Planes avoids by using explicit feature planes.&lt;SEP&gt;4D MLP is a four-dimensional multilayer perceptron whose exclusive use for the entire scene is described as wasteful and prone to over-smoothing static regions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Unbounded Scenes">
  <data key="d0">Unbounded Scenes</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Unbounded scenes are the scene setting for which MERF is described as memory-efficient.&lt;SEP&gt;Unbounded Scenes are scenes without bounded spatial extent that are handled by Mip-NeRF 360.&lt;SEP&gt;Unbounded Scenes are large-scale scenes without bounded spatial extent that MERF targets for real-time view synthesis and rendering.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Tri-Plane">
  <data key="d0">Tri-Plane</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A tri-plane is part of MERF's structure and is one of the components that K-Planes generalises to time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Sparse 3D Grid Structure">
  <data key="d0">Sparse 3D Grid Structure</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">A sparse 3D grid structure is part of MERF's design and is one of the components that K-Planes generalises to time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Time">
  <data key="d0">Time</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Time is the dimension to which K-Planes generalises the tri-plane plus sparse 3D grid structure used by MERF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">4D Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">4D Gaussian Splatting is a 2023 work by Wu et al. described as a splatting analogue that applies explicit primitives and cheap rasterisation to the dynamic case.&lt;SEP&gt;4D Gaussian Splatting is a 2023 splatting-based dynamic reconstruction method that reports real-time playback of dynamic novel views but evaluates on short captures.&lt;SEP&gt;4D Gaussian Splatting is a dynamic method described as having reused or imitated gsplat's rasteriser interface.&lt;SEP&gt;4D Gaussian Splatting is a contemporary line of dynamic methods that uses a HexPlane-style deformation field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876986</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting is a 2024 work by Duan et al. described as a splatting analogue that applies explicit primitives and cheap rasterisation to the dynamic case.&lt;SEP&gt;4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting is a 2024 splatting-based dynamic reconstruction method that reports real-time playback of dynamic novel views but evaluates on short captures.&lt;SEP&gt;4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting is one of the corpus's dynamic 3D Gaussian Splatting papers compared against hustvl/4DGaussians.&lt;SEP&gt;4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting is a dynamic Gaussian method that represents motion through anisotropic 4D XYZT Gaussians sliced at each timestamp.&lt;SEP&gt;4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting is a paper that presents 4DRotorGS, a dynamic extension of 3D Gaussian Splatting for efficient novel view synthesis in dynamic scenes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8af96ec09c34cba6b3e20e9e006eedc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eeca9db1414daed89ce6cb97dc521320&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb7662ca60286f5c929b6bb92d667dfd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/dynamic-reconstruction-scale.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/hustvl-4dgaussians/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2310-08528/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876985</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Explicit Primitives">
  <data key="d0">Explicit Primitives</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Explicit primitives are part of the trade-off used by dynamic splatting approaches such as 4D Gaussian Splatting and 4D-Rotor Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cheap Rasterisation">
  <data key="d0">Cheap Rasterisation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Cheap rasterisation is the rendering side of the trade-off applied by dynamic splatting approaches.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic Case">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic Case</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The dynamic case is the time-varying reconstruction setting to which the explicit-primitives and cheap-rasterisation trade-off is applied.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular Dynamic Capture In The Wild">
  <data key="d0">Monocular Dynamic Capture In The Wild</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Monocular dynamic capture in the wild is the demanding real-world setting whose scale and scene complexity are not matched by the cited splatting papers.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic Reconstruction Scale">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic Reconstruction Scale</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic reconstruction scale is a named question referring to the gap between current dynamic splatting benchmarks and the scale or scene complexity required for monocular dynamic capture in the wild.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Feed-Forward">
  <data key="d0">Feed-Forward</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Feed-forward refers to a class of methods highlighted as a follow-up area for benchmarking against SDS-on-splats on the same prompts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SDS-on-Splats">
  <data key="d0">SDS-on-Splats</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SDS-on-splats is a method family proposed for head-to-head benchmarking against feed-forward approaches on the same prompts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Prompts">
  <data key="d0">Prompts</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Prompts are the shared inputs on which feed-forward methods and SDS-on-splats are proposed to be benchmarked head to head.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic Capture">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic Capture</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic capture is the broader dynamic recording setting that the text says 4D Gaussian Splatting should be pushed toward at minute scale.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Short Clips">
  <data key="d0">Short Clips</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Short clips are the limited duration beyond which 4D Gaussian Splatting is said to need extension.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Minute-Scale Dynamic Capture">
  <data key="d0">Minute-Scale Dynamic Capture</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Minute-scale dynamic capture is a proposed target for advancing 4D Gaussian Splatting beyond short clips.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic Monocular Video">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic Monocular Video</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic monocular video is the monocular setting referenced by the work Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video within the dynamic line.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5bb0a18f713e04fc8443e094f65e4d3f</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W18/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874520</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
