<node id="SuGaR">
  <data key="d0">SuGaR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SuGaR is a 2023 paper presented as the surface story for splatting, regularising Gaussians toward a manifold and extracting a mesh through Poisson reconstruction on the resulting near-surface distribution.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is a 2023 splatting paper that regularises 3D Gaussians toward a manifold and then applies Poisson surface reconstruction to densely sampled near-surface points.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is follow-on work that aligns Gaussians to surfaces for mesh extraction.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is a surface-aware variant of 3D Gaussian Splatting that is described as having reused or imitated gsplat's rasteriser interface.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is a structural variant in the Gaussian Splatting literature that changes the primitive itself rather than the densification schedule.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is presented as one of the two main lines of work that bridge fast Gaussian-based radiance fields and accurate geometry.&lt;SEP&gt;SuGaR is a surface-aligned Gaussian splatting method for efficient 3D mesh reconstruction and high-quality mesh rendering from an unstructured Gaussian primitive cloud.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d445282e0f2225e2a32ef51280563a09&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2308-04079/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Poisson Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Poisson Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Poisson Reconstruction is the mesh extraction method used in SuGaR on the near-surface distribution produced by regularised Gaussians.&lt;SEP&gt;Poisson Reconstruction is a mesh reconstruction method applied to oriented Gaussian centres to generate a clean, watertight triangle mesh.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuS">
  <data key="d0">NeuS</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuS is a 2021 neural surface reconstruction method and paper for multi-view 3D reconstruction that learns high-fidelity objects and scenes from 2D image inputs. At its core, NeuS represents geometry as the zero level set of a signed distance function rather than using an occupancy field, placing it in the surface-from-volume lineage as a later development beyond methods such as UNISURF. It is commonly regarded as part of a reference line or “surface trilogy” of implicit-surface methods known for producing sharp reconstructions.

A central contribution of NeuS is its adapted, occlusion-aware volume-rendering formulation for neural implicit surfaces. The method argues that occupancy-based formulations bias surface estimation and therefore introduces an unbiased conversion from signed distance function values to density for rendering. This SDF-based formulation is presented as a cleaner derivation and a way to improve the faithfulness of surface estimation while preserving the advantages of volume-rendered learning.

NeuS is frequently used as a comparison baseline for later methods. In particular, it is described as the closest analogue to SuGaR, with SuGaR characterized as faster but more sensitive to capture conditions. More broadly, NeuS is often treated as a strong implicit-surface reference method because of its ability to produce sharp, high-quality reconstructions, though this quality comes with relatively slow training.

At the same time, reported limitations of NeuS include degraded performance in large, textureless, or sparsely captured scenes, and sensitivity to capture quality. These weaknesses help explain why it remains an important benchmark: NeuS is both a representative high-fidelity neural implicit surface method and a useful point of comparison for newer approaches that trade reconstruction sharpness, robustness, and speed differently.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuS is part of the surface-reconstruction line identified as a follow-up to Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuS is a neural-implicit-surface method that inherits the paper's Eikonal regularizer and is part of the volume-rendering era surface reconstruction lineage.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuS is a method published within days of VolSDF that addresses the same problem with a different opacity construction.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0eea83c50adbc2bba8e169fafb1efca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="2D Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">2D Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">2D Gaussian Splatting is a 2024 paper that collapses each primitive to a view-consistent oriented disk, producing cleaner geometry by removing depth ambiguity at a small cost in view-synthesis fidelity.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is a 2024 paper that collapses each primitive to a view-consistent oriented disk to reduce depth ambiguity when extracting geometry.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is follow-on work that collapses primitives to view-consistent disks for better geometry.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is a surface-aware variant of 3D Gaussian Splatting that is described as having reused or imitated gsplat's rasteriser interface.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is a structural variant in the Gaussian Splatting literature that changes the primitive itself rather than the densification schedule.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is a method that replaces each 3D volumetric Gaussian primitive with a flat oriented Gaussian disk in 3D space to provide view-consistent geometry and efficient rendering.&lt;SEP&gt;2D Gaussian Splatting is presented as one of the two main lines of work, alongside SuGaR, for extracting accurate geometry from a Gaussian field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d445282e0f2225e2a32ef51280563a09&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2308-04079/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mesh and Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Mesh and Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is the subtopic concerned with extracting cleaner geometry and meshes from splatting-based representations.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is the sub-topic assigned to the NeuS paper.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is the sub-topic assigned to the UNISURF paper.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is a section of the corpus anchored by the DTU and BlendedMVS mesh-extraction results reproduced by the repository.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is the sub-topic of the paper and the application area addressed by the method.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and Surface Reconstruction is the sub-topic assigned to the paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SLAM">
  <data key="d0">SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SLAM is the application territory identified as the next direction for investigating splatting methods.&lt;SEP&gt;SLAM is a method listed for the paper and is the broader task category in which Co-SLAM operates.&lt;SEP&gt;SLAM is the broader method category in which Point-SLAM is presented as a dense neural system for mapping and tracking.&lt;SEP&gt;SLAM is the problem setting addressed by NICE-SLAM and the related systems discussed in the text.&lt;SEP&gt;SLAM is the online estimation and mapping framework in which camera poses must be estimated from a live monocular stream without a depth sensor.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0baf845c234eac590adb7912cde85960&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a914c77868426e1f8d5848af2165c17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-14377/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-04278/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Gaussian Splatting is the central rendering and scene representation paradigm discussed in the digest, covering methods that use Gaussian primitives for real-time view synthesis, geometry recovery, and related extensions.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Splatting is a method whose repository and setup instructions are described, including training, viewing, and dataset preparation workflows.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Splatting is an alternative representation mentioned as a common substitution for a radiance field predictor in later work.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Splatting is the official implementation and rendering technique whose performance gsplat reproduces in evaluation.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian splatting is the rendering technique that the Nerfstudio team was trying to understand and that Gsplat implements as a library.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Splatting is an explicit 3D representation used by DreamGaussian as the backbone for efficient generative 3D creation.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian splatting is the rendering method that Gsplat is designed to support through CUDA-based implementation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1a8a7270af8c939590a0f9c7697a5b90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0904dcd328c5d8ef13d24665f942dc54&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22bc14784620637c470939b2097cd200&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f175249759ca8a973f8918ff16dfac34&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bfb5c9e689ffa78ae20907ec96c23e19&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8d7bbefe39a52948bd9d7195856ac2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50e33da257497d62c9963654a61913d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-25/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/graphdeco-inria-gaussian-splatting/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-06214/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nerfstudio-project-gsplat/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2309-16653/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nerfstudio-project-gsplat/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876467</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="K-Planes: Explicit Radiance Fields in Space, Time, and Appearance">
  <data key="d0">K-Planes: Explicit Radiance Fields in Space, Time, and Appearance</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">K-Planes: Explicit Radiance Fields in Space, Time, and Appearance is a paper dated 2023-01-24 that presents K-Planes for radiance fields in static 3D scenes, dynamic 4D scenes, and scenes with varying appearance.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874707</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Sara Fridovich-Keil">
  <data key="d0">Sara Fridovich-Keil</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Sara Fridovich-Keil is an author of the paper introducing K-Planes.&lt;SEP&gt;Sara Fridovich-Keil is an author of Plenoxels: Radiance Fields without Neural Networks, is listed as a joint first author, and is associated with a JAX implementation of the project.&lt;SEP&gt;Sara Fridovich-Keil is an author of Plenoxels: Radiance Fields without Neural Networks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-95e7570668ab2add22a107c42e84d859&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668</data>
