</node>
<node id="RadianceField">
  <data key="d0">RadianceField</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">RadianceField is a method label and metadata tag used to categorize papers and systems that rely on radiance-field-based 3D scene representations. In the provided descriptions, RadianceField is explicitly listed as an associated method in paper metadata for works such as NeuS, ProlificDreamer, and other referenced papers, indicating that it functions as a recognized method category rather than only a specific standalone model.

As a method category, RadianceField denotes the radiance-field approach underlying NeRF and NeRF-W, where a scene is represented as a continuous field that models geometry and appearance for view synthesis and reconstruction. In this sense, RadianceField refers broadly to the family of neural scene representation techniques built around NeRF-style formulations.

RadianceField also appears in model-specific contexts as the actual 3D representation being optimized or predicted. In Magic123, RadianceField is the neural representation optimized in the first stage to obtain rough geometry and appearance. In LRM, it is the radiance-field representation predicted for 3D reconstruction, parameterized in a NeRF-style form. In Instant3D, RadianceField is the 3D representation method predicted from sparse views. Taken together, these descriptions show that RadianceField serves both as a paper-level method tag and as a concrete neural 3D representation used within modern reconstruction and generation pipelines.&lt;SEP&gt;RadianceField is a method listed in the paper metadata as one of the methods associated with Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.&lt;SEP&gt;RadianceField is an implicit backbone used in earlier Score Distillation based 3D generation methods and is contrasted with Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cbe78430d0376f4d6a3d05234413a4a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-501dafee6515bd66912047d0b36d43f9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-11ccc947afd3d6b02019a4d324bd68d3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-faebadc81c39822f071629969e8b6a2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22bc14784620637c470939b2097cd200&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8d7bbefe39a52948bd9d7195856ac2b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2305-16213/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2008-02268/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2306-17843/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-04400/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-06214/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2309-16653/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876450</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="White-Box Pipeline">
  <data key="d0">White-Box Pipeline</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A white-box pipeline is an inspectable and regularizable pipeline that K-Planes can realize with a linear decoder and a learned global color basis.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874708</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Custom CUDA">
  <data key="d0">Custom CUDA</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Custom CUDA refers to custom CUDA code that is not required for training K-Planes in pure PyTorch.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-135c075dc7391afb1b0d603462e342e7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2301-10241/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874708</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuS: Learning Neural Implicit Surfaces by Volume Rendering for Multi-view Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">NeuS: Learning Neural Implicit Surfaces by Volume Rendering for Multi-view Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuS: Learning Neural Implicit Surfaces by Volume Rendering for Multi-view Reconstruction is a 2021 paper by Peng Wang, Lingjie Liu, Yuan Liu, Christian Theobalt, Taku Komura, and Wenping Wang about neural implicit surface reconstruction through volume rendering for multi-view reconstruction.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuS: Learning Neural Implicit Surfaces by Volume Rendering for Multi-view Reconstruction is the canonical paper associated with Totoro97/NeuS.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuS: Learning Neural Implicit Surfaces by Volume Rendering for Multi-view Reconstruction is the paper and implementation title associated with the NeuS method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0eea83c50adbc2bba8e169fafb1efca</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
