<node id="Signed Distance Function">
  <data key="d0">Signed Distance Function</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Signed Distance Function is the geometric representation used by NeuS, where the surface is defined as the zero-level set.&lt;SEP&gt;Signed distance function is a representation used by NeuS and VolSDF instead of the occupancy field used by UNISURF.&lt;SEP&gt;A signed distance function is the target behavior encouraged in a learned implicit function by Implicit Geometric Regularization.&lt;SEP&gt;Signed Distance Function is the geometry representation used by the 2021 surface trilogy for implicit-surface reconstruction.&lt;SEP&gt;Signed Distance Function is the geometric representation used by NeuS.&lt;SEP&gt;Signed Distance Function is the geometric representation from which VolSDF derives volume density and shape.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="IDR">
  <data key="d0">IDR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">IDR is a surface reconstruction method cited as providing clean, mesh-extractable geometry and as a baseline that NeuS outperforms on reconstruction quality.&lt;SEP&gt;IDR is an implicit-surface reconstruction method that reconstructs clean geometry and is matched by UNISURF without using foreground masks.&lt;SEP&gt;IDR is an external project whose data format is followed by Cameras_xxx.npz and whose code snippets are partially borrowed in the repository.&lt;SEP&gt;IDR is a neural-implicit-surface method described as a building block descendant of the paper's method.&lt;SEP&gt;IDR is a comparison method on multi-view benchmarks that requires masks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0eea83c50adbc2bba8e169fafb1efca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DVR">
  <data key="d0">DVR</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DVR is a style of surface method cited as providing clean, mesh-extractable geometry that NeuS seeks to retain without requiring masks.&lt;SEP&gt;DVR is an implicit-surface reconstruction method that produces clean geometry but requires accurate per-pixel object masks as supervision.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874861</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opacity Formulation">
  <data key="d0">Opacity Formulation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Opacity Formulation is the new SDF-driven volume-rendering formulation proposed by NeuS to avoid first-order bias in rendered surface location.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874756</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Logistic Function">
  <data key="d0">Logistic Function</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Logistic Function is the obvious SDF-to-density conversion approach discussed in the paper and is described as introducing first-order bias when used directly as in NeRF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874756</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="First-Order Bias">
  <data key="d0">First-Order Bias</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">First-Order Bias is the systematic drift in rendered surface location that arises from the naive logistic SDF-to-density approach.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874756</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DTU">
  <data key="d0">DTU</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">DTU is a dataset used in the experiments evaluating NeuS.&lt;SEP&gt;DTU is a dataset used in experiments evaluating UNISURF.&lt;SEP&gt;DTU is a dataset or benchmark whose mesh-extraction results are reproduced by the repository.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875143</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="BlendedMVS">
  <data key="d0">BlendedMVS</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">BlendedMVS is a dataset used in the experiments evaluating NeuS.&lt;SEP&gt;BlendedMVS is a dataset used in experiments evaluating UNISURF.&lt;SEP&gt;BlendedMVS is a dataset or benchmark whose mesh-extraction results are reproduced by the repository.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875143</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="UNISURF">
  <data key="d0">UNISURF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">UNISURF is a reconstruction baseline that NeuS is reported to outperform in sharpness and completeness.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is a method for multi-view reconstruction that unifies neural implicit-surface reconstruction and radiance-field volume rendering under a single formulation.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is a 2021 paper that unifies implicit surfaces and radiance fields by replacing density with an occupancy function.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is a 2021 paper in the surface trilogy that used signed distance function geometry, volume rendering, and per-scene photometric training.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is related work mentioned alongside NeuS in the context of mesh and surface reconstruction.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is a multi-view neural implicit surface method cited as sharing the same failure mode discussed in MonoSDF.&lt;SEP&gt;UNISURF is part of the surface-reconstruction line identified as a follow-up to Neural Radiance Fields.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Totoro97/NeuS">
  <data key="d0">Totoro97/NeuS</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Totoro97/NeuS is the released codebase and reference implementation of NeuS.&lt;SEP&gt;Totoro97/NeuS is an implementation that has become the de-facto baseline in surface-reconstruction benchmarks.&lt;SEP&gt;Totoro97/NeuS is a repository that provides the official implementation of NeuS and reproduces mesh-extraction results for DTU and BlendedMVS.&lt;SEP&gt;Totoro97/NeuS is a mirrored GitHub repository README for the official implementation of NeuS, with the mirror containing README text only and no code.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0eea83c50adbc2bba8e169fafb1efca</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="MonoSDF">
  <data key="d0">MonoSDF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">MonoSDF is a 2022 neural implicit surface reconstruction method and paper that builds on earlier signed distance function (SDF) based volume-rendering approaches, especially NeuS, and is commonly described as downstream or follow-on work extending that line of research. It is also referenced as related work alongside NeuS in discussions of mesh and surface reconstruction. In methodological terms, MonoSDF is characterized as inheriting key ideas from NeuS and closely related SDF frameworks such as VolSDF, including their treatment of density for surface-focused rendering, and it is described as retaining the Eikonal regularizer used in that family of methods.

The central contribution of MonoSDF is the introduction of monocular geometric cues into neural implicit surface optimization, specifically monocular depth and surface-normal supervision. By augmenting an SDF-based volume-rendering pipeline with these cues, MonoSDF aims to make implicit-surface training more tractable and practical when only a limited number of views are available, while also improving convergence and performance in challenging settings such as indoor scenes. Across the descriptions, it is consistently presented as a practical extension of prior SDF surface-reconstruction methods that improves few-view reconstruction by leveraging monocular priors.

Some descriptions additionally characterize MonoSDF as a subsequent radiance-field method using hash encoding for surface reconstruction. Taken together with the rest of the evidence, this is best understood as an additional characterization of the same broader MonoSDF line of work rather than a clearly separate entity, although the dominant and most consistent description is that MonoSDF is a 2022 SDF-based neural implicit surface reconstruction method built on NeuS-style foundations and enhanced with monocular depth and normal cues.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876833</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Voxurf">
  <data key="d0">Voxurf</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Voxurf is downstream work that extends the NeuS reference implementation.&lt;SEP&gt;Voxurf is a downstream SDF-from-multi-view method described as inheriting VolSDF or NeuS density ideas.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuS2">
  <data key="d0">NeuS2</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuS2 is downstream work that extends the NeuS reference implementation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874757</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gaussian-Splatting Surface Variants">
  <data key="d0">Gaussian-Splatting Surface Variants</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Gaussian-Splatting Surface Variants are downstream methods mentioned as extending the NeuS reference implementation.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian-Splatting surface variants are later surface-reconstruction methods described as following the recipe crystallized by MonoSDF.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian-Splatting Surface Variants are downstream surface methods described as inheriting the Laplace-CDF density or closely related constructions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="VolSDF">
  <data key="d0">VolSDF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">VolSDF is a 2021 neural implicit surface reconstruction method that explicitly represents geometry with a signed distance function and renders it through volume rendering. Published only days apart from NeuS, VolSDF is widely treated alongside NeuS as jointly establishing the signed-distance-function-via-volume-rendering paradigm for neural surface reconstruction, particularly in the line of work that followed Neural Radiance Fields.

Within the surface-from-volume lineage, VolSDF can be understood as a successor to approaches such as UNISURF: instead of using an occupancy field, it replaces that representation with a signed distance function in order to better recover surfaces. The method argues that occupancy-based formulations introduce bias in surface estimation and therefore proposes an unbiased conversion from SDF values to density for rendering. In this sense, VolSDF is part of the 2021 “surface trilogy” of methods centered on combining signed distance functions with volume rendering for accurate surface and mesh reconstruction.

VolSDF is also described as inheriting the now-standard Eikonal regularizer used in neural implicit surface learning, which further situates it in the later surface reconstruction lineage. In subsequent literature it is commonly cited as related work alongside NeuS in discussions of mesh and surface reconstruction. At the same time, later evaluations characterize VolSDF as sharing some of the same failure modes as NeuS and report that newer methods such as MonoSDF outperform it on benchmark tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;VolSDF is a volume-rendering framework that derives volume density from a signed distance function using a Laplace cumulative distribution function applied to the negative SDF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876783</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SDF-via-Volume-Rendering Paradigm">
  <data key="d0">SDF-via-Volume-Rendering Paradigm</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">SDF-via-Volume-Rendering Paradigm is the reconstruction approach defined by NeuS and VolSDF that later displaced classical MVS and original NeRF for high-fidelity multi-view surface reconstruction.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874757</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Classical MVS">
  <data key="d0">Classical MVS</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Classical MVS is an earlier multi-view reconstruction approach that the SDF-via-volume-rendering paradigm has displaced for high-fidelity surface reconstruction.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874757</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="High-Fidelity Multi-View Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">High-Fidelity Multi-View Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">High-Fidelity Multi-View Surface Reconstruction is the application area in which NeuS and related methods are positioned.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874757</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuralImplicitSurface">
  <data key="d0">NeuralImplicitSurface</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuralImplicitSurface is a method listed in the NeuS paper metadata as one of the associated methods.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuralImplicitSurface is a method tag associated with MonoSDF.&lt;SEP&gt;NeuralImplicitSurface is a method listed in the paper metadata as one of the methods associated with Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-10689/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NovelViewSynthesis">
  <data key="d0">NovelViewSynthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NovelViewSynthesis is a method listed in the NeuS paper metadata as one of the associated methods.&lt;SEP&gt;NovelViewSynthesis is a method listed for Zero-1-to-3 and refers to generating unseen views of an object.&lt;SEP&gt;NovelViewSynthesis is a method listed in the paper metadata as one of the methods associated with Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-137c1bc42e741b7a6e96b6ddc476e477&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d4bb138a75a3adf4eebfac8bdf1be29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
