  <data key="d5">1778876586</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Occupancy Field">
  <data key="d0">Occupancy Field</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Occupancy Field is a scene representation used by UNISURF that models binary inside-outside structure relaxed to a probability.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface Rendering">
  <data key="d0">Surface Rendering</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Surface rendering is a rendering regime in which opacity sharpens around a surface boundary to yield crisp reconstructions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Internal Synthetic Indoor Dataset">
  <data key="d0">Internal Synthetic Indoor Dataset</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Internal Synthetic Indoor Dataset is an internal synthetic dataset used in experiments evaluating UNISURF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Foreground Masks">
  <data key="d0">Foreground Masks</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Foreground masks are per-pixel object masks used as supervision by DVR and IDR style surface methods and not required by UNISURF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Novel View Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Novel View Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Novel View Synthesis is a computer vision and graphics task focused on generating new views of a scene from existing observations. In the provided descriptions, it is presented both as a general capability and as a methodological area recognized across multiple papers and systems. It is explicitly identified as a method associated with UNISURF, MERF, and other paper metadata entries, indicating that it is commonly used as a formal category for research contributions in scene representation and rendering.

As a technical process, Novel View Synthesis involves synthesizing unseen viewpoints by querying scene information along camera rays and compositing predictions to produce an image from a new perspective. One description characterizes this specifically as querying 5D coordinates along camera rays and combining the resulting predictions, reflecting the ray-based rendering paradigm used in neural rendering methods. More broadly, it is described as the task of generating or synthesizing new views of a scene, which captures its role as a central objective in modern 3D-aware vision systems.

The descriptions also connect Novel View Synthesis to specific applications and performance claims. It is listed as a usage area and demo mode for Zero-1-to-3, showing its role as an applied capability in interactive or demonstrative systems. It is also the rendering task for which Plenoxels is said to achieve NeRF-quality results at a fraction of the training cost, highlighting its importance as a benchmark task for evaluating efficiency and rendering quality in scene representation methods. Overall, Novel View Synthesis refers both to a core scene rendering problem and to a recognized research method area spanning multiple neural rendering papers and systems.&lt;SEP&gt;Novel View Synthesis is a task setting referenced by the paper and associated with the standard benchmarks used to evaluate the method.&lt;SEP&gt;Novel View Synthesis is a capability supported by the same Gaussian field in MonoGS and is described as high quality.&lt;SEP&gt;Novel View Synthesis is a task for which 3D Gaussian Splatting is described as excellent.&lt;SEP&gt;Novel view synthesis is a capability supported by Feature 3DGS for rendering photorealistic new viewpoints and enabling editing.&lt;SEP&gt;Novel View Synthesis is the rendering objective that the paper aims to perform efficiently for dynamic scenes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0d057f3bc5fa56c4a6477fe9f9195f8b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-252e33536ee596bbdc69a5c1521289c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eaaf691c43304c4a589967639d84b94f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6ec02429fab7e72a6a23d2a0f735836e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c8d46282ec234e9b7dfd7ddc08a05b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/cvlab-columbia-zero123/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-06405/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2403-17888/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-03203/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876987</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural Implicit Surface">
  <data key="d0">Neural Implicit Surface</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural implicit surface is listed as a method associated with the UNISURF paper and is one of the paradigms unified by UNISURF.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural Implicit Surface is a method category listed for the paper and underlies the neural scene representation used by NICE-SLAM.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural Implicit Surface is the surface representation domain addressed by the paper and by VolSDF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876783</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface-From-Volume Lineage">
  <data key="d0">Surface-From-Volume Lineage</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Surface-from-volume lineage is the research line for surface reconstruction from volume-style formulations, with UNISURF as a foundational reference and NeuS and VolSDF as follow-up methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-View Surface-Reconstruction Paradigm">
  <data key="d0">Multi-View Surface-Reconstruction Paradigm</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Multi-view surface-reconstruction paradigm is the research paradigm established by UNISURF, NeuS, and VolSDF and described as dominant in the area.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opacity Distribution">
  <data key="d0">Opacity Distribution</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Opacity distribution is the property along a ray that distinguishes surface rendering from volume rendering in the UNISURF formulation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ray Sampling">
  <data key="d0">Ray Sampling</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Ray sampling is a procedure for selecting points along rays, and in UNISURF it becomes more efficient by concentrating samples near the learned surface location.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Occupancy Boundary">
  <data key="d0">Occupancy Boundary</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Occupancy boundary is the boundary in the occupancy field around which opacity sharpens late in training and around which sampling can be concentrated.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-65491bb40aaff28e47124705eb1fff58</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-10078/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874862</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF in the Wild: Neural Radiance Fields for Unconstrained Photo Collections">
  <data key="d0">NeRF in the Wild: Neural Radiance Fields for Unconstrained Photo Collections</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF in the Wild: Neural Radiance Fields for Unconstrained Photo Collections is a paper dated 2020-08-05 that extends NeRF to unconstrained photo collections and introduces NeRF-W.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-501dafee6515bd66912047d0b36d43f9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2008-02268/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874881</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
