  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="view_data.py">
  <data key="d0">view_data.py</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">view_data.py is a script used to visualize processed data and inspect scene normalization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Floaters">
  <data key="d0">Floaters</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Floaters are visual artifacts that can result from dynamic objects, specularity, and other capture issues, and are a target for quality improvements.&lt;SEP&gt;Floaters are visually disturbing artifacts admitted by unbounded captures and suppressed by the paper's regularization method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875745</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Poor Quality Surfaces">
  <data key="d0">Poor Quality Surfaces</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Poor Quality Surfaces are degraded surface reconstruction results that can be caused by specularity and other capture issues.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Semi-Transparent Look Issue">
  <data key="d0">Semi-Transparent Look Issue</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Semi-Transparent Look Issue is a quality problem that exp activation may help reduce.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-02c51c541bd8838daa93cb2a36760941</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Parallel Compilation">
  <data key="d0">Parallel Compilation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Parallel Compilation is a compilation approach that is enabled by Ninja and significantly improves iteration speed.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-333901bdf7c8210583cee57303d02eb3</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Iteration Speed">
  <data key="d0">Iteration Speed</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Iteration Speed is the rate of development cycles and is described as significantly improved by parallel compilation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-333901bdf7c8210583cee57303d02eb3</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="sudo apt install ninja-build">
  <data key="d0">sudo apt install ninja-build</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">sudo apt install ninja-build is the command presented for installing Ninja on Ubuntu.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-333901bdf7c8210583cee57303d02eb3</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/sxyu-svox2/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874887</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Daily Digest - 2026-04-20">
  <data key="d0">Daily Digest - 2026-04-20</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Daily Digest - 2026-04-20 is a research digest covering six papers related to mesh and surface reconstruction and neural radiance fields.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874996</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Surface reconstruction is presented as the field's response to the inability of radiance fields to directly provide meshes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874996</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit Geometric Regularization">
  <data key="d0">Implicit Geometric Regularization</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Implicit Geometric Regularization is a 2020 paper described as a prerequisite for later SDF-based work because it stabilizes unconstrained shape learning.&lt;SEP&gt;Implicit Geometric Regularization is a training objective for fitting neural signed distance functions directly to raw point clouds without supervised ground-truth occupancy.&lt;SEP&gt;Implicit Geometric Regularization is a prior work by Gropp et al. from 2020 that provides the Eikonal loss used in VolSDF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eikonal Term">
  <data key="d0">Eikonal Term</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">An Eikonal term is a gradient-based regularization term used to encourage a learned implicit function to behave like a signed distance function.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874996</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Occupancy Function">
  <data key="d0">Occupancy Function</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">An occupancy function is used by UNISURF in place of density and is later argued by NeuS and VolSDF to bias surface estimates.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874998</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SDF-to-Density Conversion">
  <data key="d0">SDF-to-Density Conversion</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">SDF-to-density conversion is a method proposed by NeuS and VolSDF to obtain unbiased surface estimation from signed distance functions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874998</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface-Reconstruction Benchmarks">
  <data key="d0">Surface-Reconstruction Benchmarks</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Surface-reconstruction benchmarks are evaluation settings in which the Totoro97/NeuS implementation is described as the de-facto baseline.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874998</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular Depth And Normal Predictor">
  <data key="d0">Monocular Depth And Normal Predictor</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A monocular depth and normal predictor is used in MonoSDF as an off-the-shelf source of additional cues for SDF training.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874998</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface Optimiser">
  <data key="d0">Surface Optimiser</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A surface optimiser is the optimization process into which MonoSDF feeds monocular depth and normal predictions as additional cues.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874998</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bundle-Adjusting NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Bundle-Adjusting NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Bundle-adjusting NeRF is a method for jointly optimizing camera poses and a radiance field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Camera Poses">
  <data key="d0">Camera Poses</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Camera poses are optimization variables in BARF and are highlighted as a source of error when SfM poses are poor.&lt;SEP&gt;Camera poses are camera extrinsic parameters that BARF jointly optimizes with scene representation and recovers even when perturbed or uninitialized.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-252e33536ee596bbdc69a5c1521289c2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2104-06405/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875731</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coarse-to-Fine Positional Encoding Schedule">
  <data key="d0">Coarse-to-Fine Positional Encoding Schedule</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A coarse-to-fine positional encoding schedule is the optimization schedule used by BARF for joint pose and field optimization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SfM Poses">
  <data key="d0">SfM Poses</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">SfM poses are structure-from-motion camera poses whose poor quality is framed as a problem addressed by BARF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SLAM Literature">
  <data key="d0">SLAM Literature</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">SLAM literature is described as a later area in which the same trick used by BARF reappears.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Splatting Line">
  <data key="d0">Splatting Line</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The splatting line is presented as another research line that is about to collide with the surface line in the next week's reading.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ResearchDigest">
  <data key="d0">ResearchDigest</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">ResearchDigest is the document type assigned to the daily research digest.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mesh And Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Mesh And Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Mesh and surface reconstruction is a sub-topic of the digest and describes methods for recovering surfaces or meshes from learned scene representations.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh And Surface Reconstruction is identified as one of the sub-topics covered by the weekly synthesis and is discussed through the surface-reconstruction line absorbed by Gaussian splatting.&lt;SEP&gt;Mesh and surface reconstruction is the sub-topic assigned to MonoSDF in the metadata.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-39dac1db0f50be2348ba37c8912fe321</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2206-00665/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875634</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Learned Implicit Function">
  <data key="d0">Learned Implicit Function</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A learned implicit function is the function regularized by Implicit Geometric Regularization to behave like a signed distance function.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Unconstrained Shape Learning">
  <data key="d0">Unconstrained Shape Learning</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Unconstrained shape learning is described as becoming stable through the regularization introduced by Implicit Geometric Regularization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit Surfaces">
  <data key="d0">Implicit Surfaces</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Implicit surfaces are one of the two representation families that UNISURF is described as unifying with radiance fields.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778874999</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Density">
  <data key="d0">Density</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Density is the representation component that UNISURF replaces with an occupancy function.&lt;SEP&gt;Density is one of the themes highlighted in the discussion of splatting methods and the sparse-view frontier.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e121a6c015eb471a5abd27b987476ced&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a4716f0532d6b5d940a3893a269cfdc9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-20/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Weekly Synthesis 2026-W17">
  <data key="d0">Weekly Synthesis 2026-W17</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Weekly Synthesis 2026-W17 is a weekly synthesis document for ISO week 2026-W17 that argues 3D Gaussian Splatting is absorbing implicit-surface reconstruction and visual SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit-Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Implicit-Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Implicit-Surface Reconstruction is a line of methods treated in the NeRF era as a separate problem and commonly based on signed distance functions and volume rendering.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF Era">
  <data key="d0">NeRF Era</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF Era is the period in which view synthesis, implicit-surface reconstruction, and visual SLAM were treated as separate problems with implicit-field representations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875010</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3DGS">
  <data key="d0">3DGS</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">3DGS is a 2023 paper referenced as an anchor point for the rise of 3D Gaussian Splatting.&lt;SEP&gt;3DGS is a source project from which some code in the repository is borrowed.&lt;SEP&gt;3DGS is presented as a serious backbone for generative 3D, a position helped establish by DreamGaussian.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0d7c1d8ea46e8d39c693dee7fccbb8f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8d7bbefe39a52948bd9d7195856ac2b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/hustvl-4dgaussians/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2309-16653/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876451</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular Cues">
  <data key="d0">Monocular Cues</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Monocular Cues are additional signals used by MonoSDF to make training work with fewer views.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Feed-Forward Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Feed-Forward Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Feed-forward reconstruction is a recent architectural approach for single- or sparse-view 3D reconstruction that produces outputs without a per-scene optimisation loop and emphasizes fast inference.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Single- Or Sparse-View 3D Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Single- Or Sparse-View 3D Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Single- or sparse-view 3D reconstruction is the task domain in which the compared architectures aim to reconstruct 3D assets from limited visual input.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hong Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Hong Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Hong et al. are the authors associated with the 2023 LRM work.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-9d220499711c1162411863777d237e45</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/questions/inference-cost-vs-fidelity.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Poisson Surface Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">Poisson Surface Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Poisson Surface Reconstruction is the mesh reconstruction method applied in SuGaR after sampling near-surface points from regularised Gaussians.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Oriented Disk">
  <data key="d0">Oriented Disk</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Oriented Disk is the primitive form used in 2D Gaussian Splatting to enforce view-consistent surface-like behavior.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Depth Ambiguity">
  <data key="d0">Depth Ambiguity</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Depth Ambiguity is the geometric uncertainty associated with 3D Gaussians when geometry rather than radiance is required.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Radiance">
  <data key="d0">Radiance</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Radiance is the appearance-oriented target that contrasts with geometry extraction in splatting systems.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuS-Line Methods">
  <data key="d0">NeuS-Line Methods</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuS-Line Methods are implicit-surface reconstruction methods noted for sharper results on thin structures and self-occlusion but much slower training times.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Thin Structures">
  <data key="d0">Thin Structures</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Thin Structures are object characteristics on which NeuS-line methods still produce sharper reconstructions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-32b6f8bef5969e289e4fe3c770fb5f73</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/weekly/2026-W17/synthesis.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875011</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Self-Occlusion">
  <data key="d0">Self-Occlusion</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Self-Occlusion is an object property that remains challenging and is handled more sharply by NeuS-line methods.</data>
