<node id="Daily Digest 2026-05-05">
  <data key="d0">Daily Digest 2026-05-05</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Daily Digest 2026-05-05 is a research digest dated 2026-05-05 that covers six papers on diffusion-based 3D generation and 3D Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875137</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="2D Text-to-Image Diffusion Model">
  <data key="d0">2D Text-to-Image Diffusion Model</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A 2D Text-to-Image Diffusion Model is used as a critic that provides the prior for DreamFusion and guides renderings toward matching a text prompt.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875137</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion">
  <data key="d0">ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion is a reimplementation of DreamFusion that most people actually ran because the original DreamFusion used proprietary Imagen weights.&lt;SEP&gt;ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion is the open-source repository listed for DreamFusion in the metadata.&lt;SEP&gt;ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion is a widely used open reimplementation repository of DreamFusion: Text-to-3D using 2D Diffusion created by Jiaxiang Tang and built on Stable Diffusion rather than Google's closed Imagen model.&lt;SEP&gt;ashawkey/stable-dreamfusion is a mirrored repository entry for Stable-Dreamfusion that contains README text only, is licensed under Apache-2.0, and references arXiv-2209.14988 as the canonical paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-179a41f27c8e25c365ff0d8b13bddc43&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f98a94c0a3f79ba956d93735db4362c0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cee14ff0001178656f392a3bf199e70c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2209-14988/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875659</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Imagen">
  <data key="d0">Imagen</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Imagen is a proprietary model whose weights were used by the original DreamFusion implementation.&lt;SEP&gt;Imagen is Google's closed diffusion model that the original DreamFusion used.&lt;SEP&gt;Imagen is a model described as not publicly available and is replaced by Stable Diffusion in the implementation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f98a94c0a3f79ba956d93735db4362c0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cee14ff0001178656f392a3bf199e70c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875660</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Two-Stage Pattern">
  <data key="d0">Two-Stage Pattern</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The Two-Stage Pattern is a coarse-to-fine workflow in which a low-resolution NeRF stage is followed by a higher-resolution refinement stage, and it becomes standard.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Stable Diffusion">
  <data key="d0">Stable Diffusion</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Stable Diffusion is a publicly released diffusion-model codebase and model family that serves as a widely used foundation for text-to-image and related generative vision research. In the provided descriptions, it is characterized both as a model and as a repository or project base that other systems build upon, and it is acknowledged as an important related resource in this broader research ecosystem.

Stable Diffusion functions as the core backbone for several downstream methods. It is the diffusion model on which Stable-DreamFusion recreates the DreamFusion pipeline, replacing Imagen with a text-to-2D model that powers Stable-DreamFusion’s implementation. In that context, Stable Diffusion also acts as the guidance model during training, with support for versions 1.5, 2.0, and 2.1, and it can be swapped for a custom Hugging Face checkpoint.

Stable Diffusion also underlies Zero-1-to-3 and Magic123. Zero-1-to-3 fine-tunes Stable Diffusion for novel view synthesis, inheriting its broad object prior from the original backbone. In Magic123, Stable Diffusion contributes the 2D SDS loss, further showing its role not only as a generative model but also as a training and optimization component within 3D-aware generation pipelines. Overall, Stable Diffusion is presented as a foundational, reusable base model and code resource that enables multiple derivative systems across text-to-2D, novel-view, and 3D generation workflows.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d1cb4f77562fea889c9e32a8c9b6b118&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4cab660adb0c0033bdf9b7cb3ec02bfd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f98a94c0a3f79ba956d93735db4362c0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cee14ff0001178656f392a3bf199e70c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0ea2d1fff273acbdf62338200407400&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d4bb138a75a3adf4eebfac8bdf1be29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c47e36db5dfb4966f1d4d610b06ac6bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/cvlab-columbia-zero123/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/ashawkey-stable-dreamfusion/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2303-11328/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/cvlab-columbia-zero123/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778877000</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Camera Pose">
  <data key="d0">Camera Pose</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Camera Pose is the conditioning signal used in Zero-1-to-3 relative to a reference image.&lt;SEP&gt;Camera Pose is the current pose estimate updated by Point-SLAM through gradients from the RGBD-based re-rendering loss.&lt;SEP&gt;Camera Pose is the estimated camera state that NICE-SLAM fixes during mapping and refines during tracking.&lt;SEP&gt;Camera Pose is known geometric information used together with a monocular depth estimate to create new 3D points in LucidDreamer.&lt;SEP&gt;Camera pose is one of the predicted quantities that DROID-SLAM iteratively revises during optimization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0a914c77868426e1f8d5848af2165c17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dea341f1a2c850107557c2c2de09ba69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2304-04278/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-12130/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="cvlab-columbia/zero123">
  <data key="d0">cvlab-columbia/zero123</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">cvlab-columbia/zero123 is the implementation that became the default novel-view prior for downstream image-to-3D work.&lt;SEP&gt;cvlab-columbia/zero123 is a GitHub repository mirror that contains the README text for the Zero-1-to-3 project and states that code is not included in the mirror.&lt;SEP&gt;cvlab-columbia/zero123 is a repository described as the official release of Zero-1-to-3: Zero-shot One Image to 3D Object and provides an Objaverse-trained checkpoint and inference scripts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0d057f3bc5fa56c4a6477fe9f9195f8b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c47e36db5dfb4966f1d4d610b06ac6bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/cvlab-columbia-zero123/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/cvlab-columbia-zero123/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876990</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Novel-View Prior">
  <data key="d0">Novel-View Prior</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Novel-View Prior is the downstream image-to-3D prior for new viewpoints that cvlab-columbia/zero123 became the default implementation for.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Vanilla SDS">
  <data key="d0">Vanilla SDS</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Vanilla SDS is the baseline form of Score Distillation Sampling that is described as suffering from overly smooth, oversaturated geometry due to mode collapse.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="dreamgaussian/dreamgaussian">
  <data key="d0">dreamgaussian/dreamgaussian</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">dreamgaussian/dreamgaussian is a small and readable release associated with DreamGaussian and is recommended as a starting point for learning the sub-field.&lt;SEP&gt;dreamgaussian/dreamgaussian is a repository that contains the official implementation of DreamGaussian and is mirrored under the MIT License as README-only content.&lt;SEP&gt;dreamgaussian/dreamgaussian is the open-source repository identifier listed for DreamGaussian in the input metadata.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d585a450d31daf1370ab99c3ececfb44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8d7bbefe39a52948bd9d7195856ac2b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/dreamgaussian-dreamgaussian/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2309-16653/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876452</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Rasterisation">
  <data key="d0">Rasterisation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Rasterisation is the rendering process that makes DreamGaussian faster than NeRF-based approaches because it is faster than ray marching.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ray Marching">
  <data key="d0">Ray Marching</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Ray Marching is the slower rendering process contrasted with rasterisation in the explanation of DreamGaussian's speed advantage.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Training Data">
  <data key="d0">3D Training Data</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Training Data is the type of training data that DreamFusion is described as not requiring.&lt;SEP&gt;3D training data is the type of supervision that DreamFusion avoids using for text-to-3D generation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-179a41f27c8e25c365ff0d8b13bddc43</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2209-14988/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875233</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Textured-Mesh Refinement Stage">
  <data key="d0">Textured-Mesh Refinement Stage</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Textured-Mesh Refinement Stage is the high-resolution second stage in Magic3D that refines outputs into a textured mesh.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c9fd8d6d633ccb294d8ac229c312a9a7</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-05-05/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875139</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Arxiv-2106-10689">
  <data key="d0">Arxiv-2106-10689</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Arxiv-2106-10689 is the identifier of the canonical paper linked to Totoro97/NeuS.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875142</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Unbiased, Occlusion-Aware Volume-Rendering Scheme">
  <data key="d0">Unbiased, Occlusion-Aware Volume-Rendering Scheme</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Unbiased, Occlusion-Aware Volume-Rendering Scheme is the rendering approach used by NeuS to address limitations in earlier reconstructions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875142</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Surface-Bias Problem">
  <data key="d0">Surface-Bias Problem</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Surface-Bias Problem is the limitation in earlier NeRF-style reconstructions that NeuS is described as fixing.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875142</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF-Style Reconstructions">
  <data key="d0">NeRF-Style Reconstructions</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF-Style Reconstructions are earlier reconstruction approaches described as being limited by the surface-bias problem.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875142</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="arxiv-2106-10689">
  <data key="d0">arxiv-2106-10689</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">arxiv-2106-10689 is the canonical paper identifier associated with Totoro97/NeuS.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2c91a60b726aa8161d334939e44ec72e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/totoro97-neus/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875143</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields">
  <data key="d0">Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields is a 2021 paper that introduces a multiscale anti-aliased representation for neural radiance fields and presents Mip-NeRF as a faster, smaller, and more accurate alternative to vanilla NeRF for multi-resolution rendering.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875167</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ben Mildenhall">
  <data key="d0">Ben Mildenhall</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Ben Mildenhall is an author of Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields and is also cited in connection with NeRF (Mildenhall et al., 2020).&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is an author of DreamFusion.&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is an author of Mip-NeRF 360: Unbounded Anti-Aliased Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is an author of NeRF: Representing Scenes as Neural Radiance Fields for View Synthesis.&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is an author of MERF.&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is a listed author of the NeRF paper and is marked as an equal contributor.&lt;SEP&gt;Ben Mildenhall is an author of the cited NeRF paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-179a41f27c8e25c365ff0d8b13bddc43&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-45d73dd21f95946d74e1b943beb1d384&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ee99e1fe0369d50218c77432ff216939</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2209-14988/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/bmild-nerf/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876879</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Peter Hedman">
  <data key="d0">Peter Hedman</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Peter Hedman is an author of Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;Peter Hedman is an author of HyperNeRF.&lt;SEP&gt;Peter Hedman is an author of Mip-NeRF 360: Unbounded Anti-Aliased Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;Peter Hedman is an author of MERF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e871ba692ecdc2269f6f148bf3849940&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-13228/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Pratul P. Srinivasan">
  <data key="d0">Pratul P. Srinivasan</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Pratul P. Srinivasan is an author of Mip-NeRF: A Multiscale Representation for Anti-Aliasing Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;Pratul P. Srinivasan is an author of Mip-NeRF 360: Unbounded Anti-Aliased Neural Radiance Fields.&lt;SEP&gt;Pratul P. Srinivasan is an author of NeRF: Representing Scenes as Neural Radiance Fields for View Synthesis.&lt;SEP&gt;Pratul P. Srinivasan is an author of MERF.&lt;SEP&gt;Pratul P. Srinivasan is a listed author of the NeRF paper and is marked as an equal contributor.&lt;SEP&gt;Pratul P. Srinivasan is an author of the cited NeRF paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d0dff9058b6eb6ab9730d5170f51b92d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed61775b026776e3df7ec95d66d9c8df&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-45d73dd21f95946d74e1b943beb1d384&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ee99e1fe0369d50218c77432ff216939</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2111-12077/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2003-08934/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/bmild-nerf/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876879</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Aliasing">
  <data key="d0">Aliasing</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Aliasing is the rendering error produced when high-frequency scene content is reconstructed incorrectly across different image resolutions, causing high-frequency artifacts at low-resolution viewpoints and blur at high-resolution viewpoints.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Cone">
  <data key="d0">Cone</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Cone is the geometric primitive used by Mip-NeRF in place of a thin ray, with an apex at the camera center and a footprint matched to a pixel.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Conical Frustums">
  <data key="d0">Conical Frustums</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Conical Frustums are the sequence of volumetric regions sampled along the cone in Mip-NeRF instead of point samples.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Integrated Positional Encoding">
  <data key="d0">Integrated Positional Encoding</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Integrated Positional Encoding is the encoding used in Mip-NeRF to represent each conical frustum as the expectation of NeRF's sinusoidal positional encoding under a multivariate Gaussian approximation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multivariate Gaussian">
  <data key="d0">Multivariate Gaussian</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Multivariate Gaussian is the approximation used in Mip-NeRF to model each conical frustum when computing integrated positional encoding.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mipmapping">
  <data key="d0">Mipmapping</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Mipmapping is a classical anti-aliasing multiscale method whose behavior is matched by the damped high-frequency features produced by integrated positional encoding.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Single Network">
  <data key="d0">Single Network</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Single Network is the unified MLP architecture in Mip-NeRF that replaces the separate coarse and fine MLPs of vanilla NeRF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Standard NeRF Synthetic Dataset">
  <data key="d0">Standard NeRF Synthetic Dataset</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Standard NeRF Synthetic Dataset is the benchmark dataset on which Mip-NeRF reduces average error by 17 percent relative to vanilla NeRF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="New Multiscale Variant">
  <data key="d0">New Multiscale Variant</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">New Multiscale Variant is the multiscale dataset variant introduced by the authors on which Mip-NeRF reduces average error by 60 percent.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Brute-Force Supersampled NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Brute-Force Supersampled NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Brute-Force Supersampled NeRF is a higher-cost NeRF baseline that Mip-NeRF matches at 22 times lower cost.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="IPE Construction">
  <data key="d0">IPE Construction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">IPE Construction is the integrated positional encoding formulation for which the paper is described as the canonical reference within the corpus.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="AntiAliasing">
  <data key="d0">AntiAliasing</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">AntiAliasing is a method tag listed in the paper metadata and is a central objective of Mip-NeRF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="google/mipnerf">
  <data key="d0">google/mipnerf</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">google/mipnerf is the open-source repository identifier listed in the paper metadata for Mip-NeRF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-Scale Capture">
  <data key="d0">Multi-Scale Capture</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Multi-Scale Capture is the requirement for handling scenes observed at multiple scales or resolutions in downstream radiance-field work.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anti-Aliased Radiance-Field Variants">
  <data key="d0">Anti-Aliased Radiance-Field Variants</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Anti-Aliased Radiance-Field Variants are downstream radiance-field methods that follow Mip-NeRF in addressing aliasing across scales.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-24800bbb3bf5dc8182a3f3b86a0d5dad</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2103-13415/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875168</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Instant Neural Graphics Primitives with a Multiresolution Hash Encoding">
  <data key="d0">Instant Neural Graphics Primitives with a Multiresolution Hash Encoding</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Instant Neural Graphics Primitives with a Multiresolution Hash Encoding is a 2022 paper that presents Instant-NGP and a multiresolution hash encoding for fitting neural graphics primitives much faster than prior work without sacrificing quality.&lt;SEP&gt;Instant Neural Graphics Primitives with a Multiresolution Hash Encoding is the canonical paper associated with Instant-NGP.&lt;SEP&gt;Instant Neural Graphics Primitives with a Multiresolution Hash Encoding is the paper represented by NVlabs/instant-ngp and is cited as Müller et al., 2022.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1ce2165eaaf1422a9b02235e41e20e20</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876670</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multiresolution Hash Encoding">
  <data key="d0">Multiresolution Hash Encoding</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Multiresolution Hash Encoding is a multi-resolution hash-table encoding that maps a query 3D coordinate across multiple resolution levels to hashed grid-corner feature vectors that are interpolated and concatenated for a tiny MLP.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural Graphics Primitives">
  <data key="d0">Neural Graphics Primitives</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural Graphics Primitives are graphics representations that include radiance fields, signed distance functions, gigapixel images, and neural volumes.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural graphics primitives are the class of graphics representations implemented in Instant-NGP.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural Graphics Primitives are the visual representations explored and viewed within Instant-NGP through interactive, VR, rendering, and sharing features.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e7155c5c4414366947e20975f11efaef</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876504</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Signed Distance Functions">
  <data key="d0">Signed Distance Functions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Signed Distance Functions are one type of neural graphics primitive that Instant-NGP can fit.&lt;SEP&gt;Signed distance functions, abbreviated SDFs, are one of the four neural graphics primitives implemented in Instant-NGP.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876504</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gigapixel Images">
  <data key="d0">Gigapixel Images</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Gigapixel Images are one type of neural graphics primitive that Instant-NGP can fit.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural Volumes">
  <data key="d0">Neural Volumes</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural Volumes are one type of neural graphics primitive that Instant-NGP can fit.&lt;SEP&gt;Neural volumes are one of the four neural graphics primitives implemented in Instant-NGP.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eea3b682e8bd992578c8df7af80e379d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nvlabs-instant-ngp/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876504</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DVGO">
  <data key="d0">DVGO</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DVGO is prior work representing the explicit-grid line that the contribution intersects.&lt;SEP&gt;DVGO is a later method described as a direct descendant of Plenoxels.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0561cfd70b96f995d3cdeb043981668</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2112-05131/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875501</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fully Fused CUDA Kernels">
  <data key="d0">Fully Fused CUDA Kernels</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Fully Fused CUDA Kernels are the implementation approach used end-to-end in the system with careful attention to memory bandwidth.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nerfacto">
  <data key="d0">Nerfacto</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Nerfacto is a method whose defaults wrap the hash encoding.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2201-05989/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778875203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nerfstudio">
  <data key="d0">Nerfstudio</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Nerfstudio is a software framework whose defaults wrap the hash encoding.&lt;SEP&gt;Nerfstudio is a software dependency that is installed for preparing custom datasets.&lt;SEP&gt;Nerfstudio is the project or organization whose 3DGS training uses Gsplat as a backbone.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-71173d9786b13b28dc182e4c921d912b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5d8dc07a758da2f544255725b8c6e1a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50e33da257497d62c9963654a61913d2</data>
