<node id="PointCloud">
  <data key="d0">PointCloud</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">PointCloud is the intermediate 3D representation used in LucidDreamer, formed by lifting generated images into 3D and progressively aggregating new chunks of points.&lt;SEP&gt;PointCloud is the method tag listed in the paper metadata.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6fcd8824908a999c0b58a88cfc0f735</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2002-10099/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876529</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dreaming">
  <data key="d0">Dreaming</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Dreaming is an operation in LucidDreamer in which the current point cloud is projected to a new target view and the rendered partial masked image is used as an inpainting prompt for a diffusion model to produce a coherent novel-view image.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876027</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Alignment">
  <data key="d0">Alignment</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Alignment is an operation in LucidDreamer that merges a newly lifted chunk of points into the accumulated cloud by smoothing inconsistencies across overlapping observations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876027</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="2D Diffusion Model">
  <data key="d0">2D Diffusion Model</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">2D Diffusion Model is the general-purpose image model used by LucidDreamer to generate coherent novel-view images through inpainting prompts.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876027</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Scene-Scale 3D Training Data">
  <data key="d0">Scene-Scale 3D Training Data</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Scene-Scale 3D Training Data is the type of supervision used by prior scene-generation methods and explicitly not required by LucidDreamer.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876027</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular Depth Estimate">
  <data key="d0">Monocular Depth Estimate</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Monocular Depth Estimate is combined with a known camera pose in LucidDreamer to lift a newly generated image into 3D points.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876027</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Open-Domain 3D Content Creation">
  <data key="d0">Open-Domain 3D Content Creation</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Open-Domain 3D Content Creation is the emerging area of literature concerned with Gaussian-based methods for generating diverse 3D scenes without narrow domain restrictions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2fd2757a4334bd3990412235a6cbd419</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-13384/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876028</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Daily Digest 2026-04-30">
  <data key="d0">Daily Digest 2026-04-30</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Daily Digest 2026-04-30 is a research digest that covers six papers under the subtopics Visual SLAM and MVS and 3D Gaussian Splatting, with a focus on how neural-field representations absorbed the SLAM pipeline.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876123</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural-Field Representations">
  <data key="d0">Neural-Field Representations</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural-field representations are described as having absorbed much of the SLAM pipeline while leaving some classical components underneath.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876123</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SLAM Pipeline">
  <data key="d0">SLAM Pipeline</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The SLAM pipeline is the overall tracking and mapping process discussed in the digest, with both learned and classical components.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876123</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="princeton-vl/DROID-SLAM">
  <data key="d0">princeton-vl/DROID-SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">princeton-vl/DROID-SLAM is the released reference codebase for DROID-SLAM and is described as the cleanest deep SLAM implementation that runs in real time.&lt;SEP&gt;princeton-vl/DROID-SLAM is the code repository for DROID-SLAM, and it became a de-facto baseline for deep SLAM and a front end for radiance-field-based mapping systems.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DSO">
  <data key="d0">DSO</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DSO is a classical SLAM method referenced as having the same underlying bundle adjustment concept as DROID-SLAM.&lt;SEP&gt;DSO is a classical SLAM pipeline used as a baseline whose hand-engineered front end contrasts with the learned front end of DROID-SLAM and which suffers tracking failures on challenging benchmarks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural-Implicit SLAM">
  <data key="d0">Neural-Implicit SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural-implicit SLAM is the line of work discussed in the digest that begins with NICE-SLAM and develops through later learned scene representations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876125</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural Point Cloud">
  <data key="d0">Neural Point Cloud</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A neural point cloud is the adaptive scene representation used by Point-SLAM instead of a grid.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876125</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular SLAM Systems">
  <data key="d0">Monocular SLAM Systems</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Monocular SLAM systems are the comparison group within the corpus against which MonoGS is said to achieve the highest-quality photometric reconstructions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Motion-Blurred Or Fast-Pan Captures">
  <data key="d0">Motion-Blurred Or Fast-Pan Captures</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Motion-blurred or fast-pan captures are the challenging camera-motion cases that the digest notes are not aggressively benchmarked by the discussed systems.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Recurrent Update Operator">
  <data key="d0">Recurrent Update Operator</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The recurrent update operator is the learned mechanism in DROID-SLAM that jointly refines depth and pose through a differentiable bundle adjustment layer.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Depth">
  <data key="d0">Depth</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Depth is one of the scene variables jointly refined within DROID-SLAM through the recurrent update process.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Pose">
  <data key="d0">Pose</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Pose is one of the camera-state variables jointly refined within DROID-SLAM through the recurrent update process.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hierarchical Voxel Grid Of Features">
  <data key="d0">Hierarchical Voxel Grid Of Features</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A hierarchical voxel grid of features is the scene representation used by NICE-SLAM and is optimized online for mapping and tracking.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Sparse Parametric Encoding">
  <data key="d0">Sparse Parametric Encoding</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Sparse parametric encoding is the speed-oriented representation strategy re-introduced by Co-SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit Volume">
  <data key="d0">Implicit Volume</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">An implicit volume is the scene representation that GS-SLAM and MonoGS replace with explicit 3D Gaussians.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Photometric Reconstructions">
  <data key="d0">Photometric Reconstructions</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Photometric reconstructions are the visual reconstruction outputs for which MonoGS is reported to achieve the highest quality among monocular SLAM systems in the corpus.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c5c7f1e459e9c1753c0a4eb10eae7e1d</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-30/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876126</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Christian Reiser">
  <data key="d0">Christian Reiser</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Christian Reiser is an author of MERF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Richard Szeliski">
  <data key="d0">Richard Szeliski</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Richard Szeliski is an author of MERF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Consumer GPUs">
  <data key="d0">Consumer GPUs</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Consumer GPUs are the hardware platforms whose memory budget MERF is designed to fit.&lt;SEP&gt;Consumer GPUs are the class of hardware on which the method is described as tractable for multi-second captures.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb7662ca60286f5c929b6bb92d667dfd</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2310-08528/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876658</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Browser Rendering">
  <data key="d0">Browser Rendering</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Browser Rendering is the interactive rendering environment in which MERF operates in real time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coarse Sparse 3D Feature Grid">
  <data key="d0">Coarse Sparse 3D Feature Grid</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The Coarse Sparse 3D Feature Grid is an explicit structure in MERF that stores volumetric content near surfaces while pruning empty space.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Three High-Resolution 2D Feature Planes">
  <data key="d0">Three High-Resolution 2D Feature Planes</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The Three High-Resolution 2D Feature Planes are explicit structures in MERF that add fine detail at near-zero additional memory cost.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Contraction Function">
  <data key="d0">Contraction Function</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The Contraction Function is a MERF component that maps world coordinates into a bounded volume while preserving efficient ray-box intersection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ray-Box Intersection">
  <data key="d0">Ray-Box Intersection</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Ray-Box Intersection is a geometric operation whose efficiency is preserved by MERF's contraction function for fast traversal.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D-Gaussian-Splatting Variants">
  <data key="d0">3D-Gaussian-Splatting Variants</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">3D-Gaussian-Splatting Variants are later methods whose production baking pipelines are described as inheriting from MERF's approach.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Large-Scale 360-Degree Captures">
  <data key="d0">Large-Scale 360-Degree Captures</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Large-Scale 360-Degree Captures are scene captures that Mip-NeRF 360 made tractable to reconstruct and that prior baked NeRF methods do not scale to render in real time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bounded Objects">
  <data key="d0">Bounded Objects</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Bounded Objects are spatially limited scenes or objects for which PlenOctrees and SNeRG can bake NeRF for real-time rendering.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-27c8a391c236226d67322607a99b2e56</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2302-12249/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876128</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mathematical Supplement for the gsplat Library">
  <data key="d0">Mathematical Supplement for the gsplat Library</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Mathematical Supplement for the gsplat Library is a self-contained mathematical reference that documents the forward and backward passes, rendering details, and implementation-aligned equations for the gsplat library.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Vickie Ye">
  <data key="d0">Vickie Ye</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Vickie Ye is a co-author of Mathematical Supplement for the gsplat Library.&lt;SEP&gt;Vickie Ye is listed as an author of the Gsplat white paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bfb5c9e689ffa78ae20907ec96c23e19</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/nerfstudio-project-gsplat/readme.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876415</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="gsplat">
  <data key="d0">gsplat</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">gsplat is a modular differentiable GaussianSplatting library hosted by the nerfstudio project, with a Python API that exposes forward and backward pass components individually.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nerfstudio Project">
  <data key="d0">Nerfstudio Project</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Nerfstudio Project is the project that hosts the gsplat library.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Original 3DGS Paper">
  <data key="d0">Original 3DGS Paper</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">The Original 3DGS Paper is an earlier paper by Kerbl et al. that introduces the representation and high-level rendering pipeline for 3D Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Kerbl Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Kerbl Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Kerbl Et Al. are the authors of the Original 3DGS Paper.&lt;SEP&gt;Kerbl et al. are the authors associated with the original 3D Gaussian Splatting paper that introduced Adaptive Density Control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Projection of 3D Gaussians Into Screen Space">
  <data key="d0">Projection of 3D Gaussians Into Screen Space</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Projection of 3D Gaussians Into Screen Space is a method documented in the supplement for mapping 3D Gaussians under a pinhole camera.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Pinhole Camera">
  <data key="d0">Pinhole Camera</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Pinhole Camera is the camera model used in the supplement's explanation of projecting 3D Gaussians into screen space.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Local Affine Approximation of the Perspective Transform">
  <data key="d0">Local Affine Approximation of the Perspective Transform</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Local Affine Approximation of the Perspective Transform is a method used in the supplement to describe perspective transformation during projection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Covariance Propagation">
  <data key="d0">Covariance Propagation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Covariance Propagation is the process described in the supplement for carrying covariance through the perspective transform.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Tile-Based Rasterisation">
  <data key="d0">Tile-Based Rasterisation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Tile-Based Rasterisation is a rendering method covered in the supplement and reused through gsplat's rasteriser interface.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Front-to-Back Alpha Compositing">
  <data key="d0">Front-to-Back Alpha Compositing</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Front-to-Back Alpha Compositing is a compositing method documented in the supplement as part of the rendering pipeline.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gradient Flow">
  <data key="d0">Gradient Flow</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Gradient Flow refers to the exact backward propagation described in the supplement through opacity, colour, position, scale, and rotation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Colour">
  <data key="d0">Colour</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Colour is one of the parameter components through which exact gradient flow is documented in the supplement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Position">
  <data key="d0">Position</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Position is one of the parameter components through which exact gradient flow is documented in the supplement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Scale">
  <data key="d0">Scale</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Scale is one of the parameter components through which exact gradient flow is documented in the supplement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Rotation">
  <data key="d0">Rotation</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Rotation is one of the parameter components through which exact gradient flow is documented in the supplement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876134</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Spherical-Harmonic Colour Evaluation">
  <data key="d0">Spherical-Harmonic Colour Evaluation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Spherical-Harmonic Colour Evaluation is a method documented in the supplement together with its gradients and basis convention choices.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3243555eac5ed46cea7fe8cead1666bc</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-02121/paper.md</data>
