  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Samuel Rota Bulò">
  <data key="d0">Samuel Rota Bulò</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Samuel Rota Bulò is an author of Revising Densification in Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Lorenzo Porzi">
  <data key="d0">Lorenzo Porzi</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Lorenzo Porzi is an author of Revising Densification in Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Peter Kontschieder">
  <data key="d0">Peter Kontschieder</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Peter Kontschieder is an author of Revising Densification in Gaussian Splatting.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Adaptive Density Control">
  <data key="d0">Adaptive Density Control</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Adaptive Density Control is a heuristic used in 3D Gaussian Splatting to govern when primitives are cloned, split, or pruned during training based on positional-gradient magnitudes.&lt;SEP&gt;Adaptive Density Control is a reference method introduced by the repository and used as a foundational component in downstream 3DGS methods.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a77bbc3a5c1fbf4a8a4029857b6fa01b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/graphdeco-inria-gaussian-splatting/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876956</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Original 3D Gaussian Splatting Paper">
  <data key="d0">Original 3D Gaussian Splatting Paper</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">The Original 3D Gaussian Splatting Paper is the work by Kerbl et al. that introduced Adaptive Density Control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Positional-Gradient Magnitudes">
  <data key="d0">Positional-Gradient Magnitudes</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Positional-gradient magnitudes are the trigger signal used by Adaptive Density Control to decide densification actions during training.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Pixel Reconstruction Error">
  <data key="d0">Per-Pixel Reconstruction Error</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-pixel reconstruction error is identified as the quantity that actually matters for density control because it measures how poorly the rendered output is explained.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Pixel-Error-Driven Density Control">
  <data key="d0">Pixel-Error-Driven Density Control</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Pixel-error-driven density control is the paper's proposed formulation in which densification is triggered by an auxiliary per-pixel error function computed during training.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Auxiliary Per-Pixel Error Function">
  <data key="d0">Auxiliary Per-Pixel Error Function</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The auxiliary per-pixel error function is a training-time function used to trigger densification according to reconstruction error.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Scene Primitive Cap">
  <data key="d0">Per-Scene Primitive Cap</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The per-scene primitive cap is a complementary mechanism that limits the total number of primitives generated per scene to control the speed and quality trade-off.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opacity Handling Bias">
  <data key="d0">Opacity Handling Bias</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Opacity handling bias is a flaw in Adaptive Density Control cloning operations that inadvertently doubles effective opacity contributions and skews optimization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Floating Gaussians">
  <data key="d0">Floating Gaussians</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Floating Gaussians are artefacts described as one consequence of the biased proxy used by Adaptive Density Control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Under-Densified Regions">
  <data key="d0">Under-Densified Regions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Under-densified regions are scene areas where missing structure can appear because of biased density control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Runaway Primitive Counts">
  <data key="d0">Runaway Primitive Counts</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Runaway primitive counts are excessive increases in the number of primitives that can occur in scenes with many high-frequency details under Adaptive Density Control.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Standard Novel View Synthesis Benchmarks">
  <data key="d0">Standard Novel View Synthesis Benchmarks</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Standard Novel View Synthesis benchmarks are evaluation datasets on which the method shows consistent quality improvements.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-add2de44399af98e378bc92e1b3f3d85</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2404-06109/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876239</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Chen Gao">
  <data key="d0">Chen Gao</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Chen Gao is an author of Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Ayush Saraf">
  <data key="d0">Ayush Saraf</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Ayush Saraf is an author of Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Johannes Kopf">
  <data key="d0">Johannes Kopf</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Johannes Kopf is an author of Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Jia-Bin Huang">
  <data key="d0">Jia-Bin Huang</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Jia-Bin Huang is an author of Dynamic View Synthesis from Dynamic Monocular Video.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Space-Time Novel View Synthesis">
  <data key="d0">Space-Time Novel View Synthesis</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Space-Time Novel View Synthesis is the task of synthesizing novel views over time from visual observations of a dynamic scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876308</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic Scene">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic Scene</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic Scene is a scene containing time-varying content that must be modeled across space and time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Static NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Static NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Static NeRF is the time-invariant neural radiance field component that captures static geometry and appearance in the scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dynamic NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Dynamic NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Dynamic NeRF is the time-conditioned neural radiance field component that captures time-varying parts of the scene and predicts blending weights.&lt;SEP&gt;Dynamic NeRF is a prior dynamic scene method that generally encodes motion through a canonical 3D representation and a deformation field.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-393d4b1d50fb3d20d718f84708cec66c</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2402-03307/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876985</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Time Embedding">
  <data key="d0">Time Embedding</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Time Embedding is the conditioning signal used by the dynamic neural radiance field to model temporal variation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Unsupervised Blending Weight">
  <data key="d0">Unsupervised Blending Weight</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Unsupervised Blending Weight is the predicted weight used by the renderer to composite contributions from the static and dynamic fields.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-Frame Parallax">
  <data key="d0">Multi-Frame Parallax</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Multi-Frame Parallax is the cross-frame geometric cue that benefits the static neural radiance field in the decomposition.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D Scene Flow Consistency">
  <data key="d0">3D Scene Flow Consistency</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">3D Scene Flow Consistency is a regularizer enforcing consistency of scene motion between adjacent frames.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Depth-Order Constraint">
  <data key="d0">Depth-Order Constraint</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Depth-Order Constraint is a regularizer derived from monocular depth predictions to bias reconstruction toward physically plausible depth ordering.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monocular Depth Predictions">
  <data key="d0">Monocular Depth Predictions</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Monocular Depth Predictions are depth estimates used to derive the depth-order constraint.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="2D Optical-Flow Loss">
  <data key="d0">2D Optical-Flow Loss</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">2D Optical-Flow Loss is a regularizer that ties dynamic-field motion to external optical-flow estimates.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Off-The-Shelf Flow Estimates">
  <data key="d0">Off-The-Shelf Flow Estimates</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Off-The-Shelf Flow Estimates are external motion estimates used to supervise the dynamic field through the optical-flow loss.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Casually Captured Monocular Videos">
  <data key="d0">Casually Captured Monocular Videos</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Casually Captured Monocular Videos are the evaluation videos on which the paper reports quantitative results demonstrating plausible space-time interpolation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NSFF">
  <data key="d0">NSFF</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NSFF is a follow-up method cited as part of the wave of work seeded by the paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Static/Dynamic Split">
  <data key="d0">Static/Dynamic Split</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Static/Dynamic Split is the architectural decomposition introduced by the paper that separates static and time-varying scene content.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-61a153082bbdd12d0fece3ecc8442ad9</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2105-06468/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876311</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Hidenobu Matsuki">
  <data key="d0">Hidenobu Matsuki</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Hidenobu Matsuki is an author of Gaussian Splatting SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Riku Murai">
  <data key="d0">Riku Murai</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Riku Murai is an author of Gaussian Splatting SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Paul H. J. Kelly">
  <data key="d0">Paul H. J. Kelly</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Paul H. J. Kelly is an author of Gaussian Splatting SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Andrew J. Davison">
  <data key="d0">Andrew J. Davison</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Andrew J. Davison is an author of Gaussian Splatting SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876348</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="3D GaussianSplatting">
  <data key="d0">3D GaussianSplatting</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">3D GaussianSplatting is the sole scene representation used by MonoGS and is rendered differentiably for camera tracking and mapping.&lt;SEP&gt;3D GaussianSplatting is a static Gaussian rendering method that the paper extends to dynamic scenes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb7662ca60286f5c929b6bb92d667dfd</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2310-08528/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876657</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gaussian Map">
  <data key="d0">Gaussian Map</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The Gaussian Map is the map representation against which camera tracking is performed directly in MonoGS.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Map is the current map representation in GS-SLAM against which tracking re-renders observations and visualises the scene.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876848</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gaussian Field">
  <data key="d0">Gaussian Field</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The Gaussian Field is the unified representation in MonoGS that supports tracking, mapping, and novel view synthesis.&lt;SEP&gt;A Gaussian Field is the Gaussian-based scene representation from which accurate geometry is extracted in SuGaR and related methods.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian field is the resulting 3D representation in Feature 3DGS that renders photorealistic novel views and consistent semantic features from any viewpoint.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c8d46282ec234e9b7dfd7ddc08a05b</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-03203/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876925</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Tracking">
  <data key="d0">Tracking</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Tracking is a MonoGS function that minimises a photometric loss between the current frame and a render of the current map from a candidate pose.&lt;SEP&gt;Tracking is the GS-SLAM loop that estimates a new camera pose by minimising a photometric-and-depth re-rendering loss against the current Gaussian map.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876848</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mapping">
  <data key="d0">Mapping</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Mapping is a MonoGS function that grows new Gaussians where the map fails to explain incoming pixels and updates existing Gaussians through splatting optimisation.&lt;SEP&gt;Mapping is the GS-SLAM loop that adaptively expands the scene representation by adding and pruning Gaussians according to incoming observations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876848</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Geometric Verification">
  <data key="d0">Geometric Verification</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Geometric Verification is an explicit step introduced by the authors to exploit the primitive nature of Gaussians and suppress monocular reconstruction ambiguities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876350</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Regularisation">
  <data key="d0">Regularisation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Regularisation is an explicit step introduced by the authors to exploit the primitive nature of Gaussians and suppress monocular reconstruction ambiguities.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876350</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="RGB-D Sensor">
  <data key="d0">RGB-D Sensor</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">An RGB-D Sensor is an optional sensor whose depth data can be accepted by the same MonoGS machinery as additional supervision without architectural change.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876350</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Depth Supervision Signal">
  <data key="d0">Depth Supervision Signal</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Depth Supervision Signal is the additional supervision accepted by the system when an RGB-D sensor is available.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876350</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit Neural SLAM Methods">
  <data key="d0">Implicit Neural SLAM Methods</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Implicit Neural SLAM Methods are contrasted with MonoGS as methods that struggle with tiny and transparent objects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-5a20b3ebc3dcc9adfa50adfa770ad6d2</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2312-06741/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876350</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
