  <data key="d5">1778876671</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Dense Bundle Adjustment">
  <data key="d0">Dense Bundle Adjustment</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Dense Bundle Adjustment is a learned layer coupled within DROID-SLAM to support visual SLAM performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Dense Bundle Adjustment is a differentiable optimization layer embedded at the core of DROID-SLAM and used to enforce geometrically consistent solutions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md&lt;SEP&gt;examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Recurrent Optical Flow Updates">
  <data key="d0">Recurrent Optical Flow Updates</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Recurrent Optical Flow Updates are used within DROID-SLAM and are described as a descendant of RAFT.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-a57ecf4979daf463711507fe01462548</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/repos/princeton-vl-droid-slam/about.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876675</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Daily Digest 2026-04-10">
  <data key="d0">Daily Digest 2026-04-10</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Daily Digest 2026-04-10 is a research digest that reviews five foundational papers related to neural radiance fields, visual SLAM and MVS, and dynamic and 4D reconstruction.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876753</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF Paper">
  <data key="d0">NeRF Paper</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF Paper is the original NeRF work described as a foundational paper and as an anchor for understanding later fast NeRF research.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876753</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeRF in the Wild">
  <data key="d0">NeRF in the Wild</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">NeRF in the Wild is a paper that extends NeRF to unconstrained photo collections by adding per-image appearance and transient embeddings.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876753</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coarse-to-Fine Importance Sampling">
  <data key="d0">Coarse-to-Fine Importance Sampling</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Coarse-to-Fine Importance Sampling is a method used along each ray in NeRF and described as one of the under-credited ideas later fast NeRF papers reacted to.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876754</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Coordinate MLPs">
  <data key="d0">Coordinate MLPs</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Coordinate MLPs are neural function approximators that, in this context, can fit high frequencies when aided by sinusoidal positional encoding.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876754</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Image Appearance Embeddings">
  <data key="d0">Per-Image Appearance Embeddings</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-Image Appearance Embeddings are latent components added in NeRF in the Wild to model variable capture conditions across images.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876754</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Transient Embeddings">
  <data key="d0">Transient Embeddings</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Transient Embeddings are latent components added in NeRF in the Wild to account for transient scene elements such as moving tourists and occluders.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876754</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Frame Latent">
  <data key="d0">Per-Frame Latent</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-Frame Latent is a modeling mechanism that allows scene content to be decoupled from capture conditions in unconstrained image collections.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876754</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Observation Deformation Field">
  <data key="d0">Per-Observation Deformation Field</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-Observation Deformation Field is a method in Nerfies that warps a canonical radiance field for each observation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Canonical Radiance Field">
  <data key="d0">Canonical Radiance Field</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Canonical Radiance Field is the base scene representation that Nerfies deforms to model dynamic scenes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D Reconstruction">
  <data key="d0">4D Reconstruction</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">4D Reconstruction is the reconstruction of scenes across space and time, described here as the result of applying Nerfies to casually captured selfie videos.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Visual Odometry">
  <data key="d0">Visual Odometry</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Visual Odometry is the task of estimating motion from visual input and is represented by Direct Sparse Odometry as a non-learned baseline.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Differentiable SfM">
  <data key="d0">Differentiable SfM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Differentiable SfM is a learned structure-from-motion approach whose importance is revisited through DeepV2D.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Learned Differentiable Bundle Adjustment">
  <data key="d0">Learned Differentiable Bundle Adjustment</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Learned Differentiable Bundle Adjustment is the optimization approach that DeepV2D is described as seriously attempting for the first time.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Mildenhall Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Mildenhall Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Mildenhall Et Al. are the authors credited with the original NeRF paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Martin-Brualla Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Martin-Brualla Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Martin-Brualla Et Al. are the authors credited with NeRF in the Wild.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Park Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Park Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Park Et Al. are the authors credited with Nerfies.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Engel Et Al.">
  <data key="d0">Engel Et Al.</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Engel Et Al. are the authors credited with Direct Sparse Odometry.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Fast NeRF">
  <data key="d0">Fast NeRF</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Fast NeRF is a line of later NeRF papers described as reacting to core ideas from the original NeRF paper by modifying them rather than inventing something orthogonal.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-bb1234ddae6b39821bcc34ebe785c813</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/daily/2026-04-10/digest.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876755</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Stereo Streams">
  <data key="d0">Stereo Streams</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Stereo streams are a test-time input modality that DROID-SLAM can ingest to improve accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876760</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="RGB-D Streams">
  <data key="d0">RGB-D Streams</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">RGB-D streams are a test-time input modality that DROID-SLAM can ingest to improve accuracy.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876760</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ORB-SLAM">
  <data key="d0">ORB-SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">ORB-SLAM is a classical SLAM pipeline used as a baseline whose hand-engineered front end contrasts with the learned front end of DROID-SLAM and which suffers tracking failures on challenging benchmarks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="RAFT Optical-Flow Networks">
  <data key="d0">RAFT Optical-Flow Networks</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">RAFT optical-flow networks are a prior neural architecture that contributes ideas to the DROID-SLAM design.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="ConvGRU Update Operator">
  <data key="d0">ConvGRU Update Operator</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The ConvGRU update operator is the module in DROID-SLAM that inspects frame-pair correlations in a co-visibility graph and emits updates to depth and camera pose.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="4D Correlation Volume">
  <data key="d0">4D Correlation Volume</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The 4D correlation volume is the representation computed between pairs of frames in a growing co-visibility graph and inspected by the ConvGRU update operator.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Co-Visibility Graph">
  <data key="d0">Co-Visibility Graph</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The co-visibility graph is the growing graph over frames in which DROID-SLAM computes pairwise correlations for iterative refinement.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Per-Pixel Depth">
  <data key="d0">Per-Pixel Depth</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Per-pixel depth is one of the predicted quantities that DROID-SLAM iteratively revises during optimization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gauss-Newton Step">
  <data key="d0">Gauss-Newton Step</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The Gauss-Newton step is the optimization procedure solved by the Dense Bundle Adjustment layer to project updates onto geometrically consistent solutions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DeepFactors">
  <data key="d0">DeepFactors</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DeepFactors is a prior deep SLAM approach that is reported as less accurate than DROID-SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="TANDEM">
  <data key="d0">TANDEM</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">TANDEM is a prior deep SLAM approach that is reported as less accurate than DROID-SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="DeepFusion">
  <data key="d0">DeepFusion</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">DeepFusion is a prior deep SLAM approach that is reported as less accurate than DROID-SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876761</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Deep SLAM">
  <data key="d0">Deep SLAM</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Deep SLAM is the research area for which the DROID-SLAM codebase became a de-facto baseline.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Radiance-Field-Based Mapping Systems">
  <data key="d0">Radiance-Field-Based Mapping Systems</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Radiance-field-based mapping systems are a class of mapping systems that use the DROID-SLAM codebase as a front end.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Direct Sparse Odometry (DSO)">
  <data key="d0">Direct Sparse Odometry (DSO)</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Direct Sparse Odometry (DSO) is a classical baseline contrasted with DROID-SLAM and is associated with catastrophic tracking failures on challenging benchmarks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7411808cb359d1b718d660e9dbd2a39e</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2108-10869/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876762</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="SuGaR: Surface-Aligned Gaussian Splatting for Efficient 3D Mesh Reconstruction and High-Quality Mesh Rendering">
  <data key="d0">SuGaR: Surface-Aligned Gaussian Splatting for Efficient 3D Mesh Reconstruction and High-Quality Mesh Rendering</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">SuGaR: Surface-Aligned Gaussian Splatting for Efficient 3D Mesh Reconstruction and High-Quality Mesh Rendering is a paper describing a method that aligns Gaussians to scene surfaces and extracts editable meshes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Antoine Guédon">
  <data key="d0">Antoine Guédon</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Antoine Guédon is an author of the SuGaR paper and is associated with the development of the SuGaR method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Vincent Lepetit">
  <data key="d0">Vincent Lepetit</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Vincent Lepetit is an author of the SuGaR paper and is associated with the development of the SuGaR method.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Neural SDFs">
  <data key="d0">Neural SDFs</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Neural SDFs are implicit scene representation methods for which Marching Cubes is the default mesh extraction approach.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Regularisation Term">
  <data key="d0">Regularisation Term</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The Regularisation Term is a component of SuGaR that encourages Gaussians to align with the underlying scene surface by penalising elongation that deviates from the local tangent plane.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876772</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Oriented Gaussian Centres">
  <data key="d0">Oriented Gaussian Centres</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Oriented Gaussian Centres are the trained Gaussian centre data used as input to Poisson Reconstruction in SuGaR.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Refinement Stage">
  <data key="d0">Refinement Stage</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">The Refinement Stage is an optional SuGaR procedure that binds Gaussians to the extracted mesh and jointly optimises the mesh and Gaussians.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Barycentric Coordinate">
  <data key="d0">Barycentric Coordinate</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A Barycentric Coordinate is the face-based parameter used in the refinement stage to attach each Gaussian primitive to the extracted mesh surface.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Editable Gaussian Assets">
  <data key="d0">Editable Gaussian Assets</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Editable Gaussian Assets are Gaussian-based scene assets for which the released SuGaR code serves as a common reference.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anttwo/SuGaR">
  <data key="d0">Anttwo/SuGaR</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">Anttwo/SuGaR is the open-source repository associated with the SuGaR paper and its released code.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c76c39f593d0f7cf762ef607bb98a3db</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-12775/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Volume Rendering of Neural Implicit Surfaces">
  <data key="d0">Volume Rendering of Neural Implicit Surfaces</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Volume Rendering of Neural Implicit Surfaces is a paper published on 2021-06-22 about rendering and reconstructing neural implicit surfaces.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876783</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Jiatao Gu">
  <data key="d0">Jiatao Gu</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Jiatao Gu is an author of Volume Rendering of Neural Implicit Surfaces.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876783</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Yoni Kasten">
  <data key="d0">Yoni Kasten</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Yoni Kasten is an author of Volume Rendering of Neural Implicit Surfaces.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876783</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Laplace Cumulative Distribution Function">
  <data key="d0">Laplace Cumulative Distribution Function</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Laplace Cumulative Distribution Function is the transformation applied to the negative signed distance function to produce VolSDF density.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bandwidth Parameter">
  <data key="d0">Bandwidth Parameter</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Bandwidth Parameter is the learnable parameter that controls the sharpness of the thin high-density shell in VolSDF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Opacity-Approximation Error Bound">
  <data key="d0">Opacity-Approximation Error Bound</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Opacity-Approximation Error Bound is the explicit bound derived in VolSDF along a ray in terms of the bandwidth.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Importance Sampler">
  <data key="d0">Importance Sampler</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Importance Sampler is the sampling method enabled by the opacity-approximation error bound to place samples efficiently along a ray.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Eikonal Loss">
  <data key="d0">Eikonal Loss</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Eikonal Loss is the regularization loss used to keep the signed distance function metric in VolSDF.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="NeuralWarp">
  <data key="d0">NeuralWarp</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">NeuralWarp is a downstream SDF-from-multi-view method described as inheriting VolSDF or NeuS density ideas.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Masks">
  <data key="d0">Masks</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Masks are required by IDR on the standard multi-view benchmarks mentioned in the paper.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-62f6aaf4d349907fedafca12c9a53bdb</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2106-12052/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876784</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="GS-SLAM: Dense Visual SLAM with 3D Gaussian Splatting">
  <data key="d0">GS-SLAM: Dense Visual SLAM with 3D Gaussian Splatting</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">GS-SLAM: Dense Visual SLAM with 3D Gaussian Splatting is a paper describing GS-SLAM and its use of explicit Gaussian primitives for dense visual SLAM.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ef4e01183cb872fcf6e3325fde57a921</data>
  <data key="d4">examples/demo-corpus/data/research/papers/arxiv-2311-11700/paper.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1778876847</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
